<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Holds Steady at 4.5 pct in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate
remained steady at 4.5 percent in July, despite of the impact of
the General Motor strikes, which caused the worst factory job
losses in 16 years, the Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The latest report matched June's seasonally adjusted rate and
was only slightly higher than the 28-year low of 4.3 percent,
recorded in May, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
In July, U.S. employers reported a net gain in jobs of only
66,000, the weakest month in two and a half years. Job growth was
held back by a drop of 176,000 in manufacturing, the largest since
October 1982.
</P>
<P>
The department attributed 146,600 of the loss to the direct or
indirect impact of the GM strikes, which began June 5, and were
settled last week.
</P>
<P>
Auto manufacturing alone suffered a drop of 111,000 jobs but
other industries that supply GM, the nation's largest corporation,
were forced to lay off their workers. The electronic components
and food industries as well as textile mills also lost jobs.
</P>
<P>
However, the aircraft industry and printing and publishing
added jobs. So did construction firms, up 18,000.
</P>
<P>
Government payrolls decreased by 12,000 positions, but many
service industries still are expanding robustly. Retail employment
increased by 125,000, including 69,000 jobs at restaurants and
bars.
</P>
<P>
Employment dipped at nursing homes and in home health care but
engineering and management services and computer services both
continued a long-term trend of strong growth. There were 32,000
new jobs in finance, insurance and real estate.
</P>
<P>
However, the better-than-expected situation in labor market
could revive concern that scarce labor will pressure wages higher,
crimping corporate profits and contributing to increased
inflation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
