<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Water Levels Jump Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Flood situation has worsen in
central China's Hubei Province on Friday night as water levels of
Yangtze River surged to new heights, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
At 22:00 pm, water level at the Shashi Measuring Point,
upstream of Wuhan, the provincial capital, climbed to 44.88 m,
compared with 44.81 m at 19:00 pm.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, water level at Yichang, upstream of Shashi,
rose to 53.93 m, 0.77 m higher than the level on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Shashi has further approached the level for
a proposed diversion plan to discharge flood waters into the
Jingjiang diversion zone, in Gong'an County, about 200 kilometers
of Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
Some 250,000 local residents in the zone have been evacuated to
make way for the diversion so far. A total of 330,000 people are
expected to be resettled from the diversion area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
