<HEADLINE> Clinton Condemns Embassies Bombings as "Inhumane" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Friday condemned two terrorist attacks that killed dozens of
people at the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, and vowed to
do everything in his power to find the people behind the bombings.
</P>
<P>
"These acts of terrorist violence are abhorrent, they are
inhumane," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"We will use all the means at our disposal to bring those
responsible to justice nor matter what or how long it takes,"
the president added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was awaken by a phone call at 5:30 from National
Security Adviser Sandy Berger who informed him of the bombings
at the U.S. embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and in Dar-es-Salaam,
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman P.J. Crowley told reporters that
Clinton, when informed of the tragedy, was "deeply troubled."
</P>
<P>
"We're treating this as a terrorist attack," Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been no claim of responsibility for the
explosions and would not comment on who the United States
suspected was behind the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Crowley said U.S. military aircraft would fly to the scene to
bring medical supplies and blood and be able to evacuate the
wounded.
</P>
<P>
He said stepped-up security measures were being taken at U.S.
embassies throughout the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
