<HEADLINE> U.S. Retailers Post Strong Sales for July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Most major U.S. retailers posted
strong sales in July, beating many pessimistic estimates and
showing that the consumer still strongly underpins the economy.
</P>
<P>
Results were strong across nearly all retail categories, from
discounters and department stores to speciality apparel and
electronics stores, according to statistics published by the Wall
Street Journal today.
</P>
<P>
Sales at stores open at least one year rose 5.7 percent in July,
up from 5.5 percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Many retailers said that their results were above expectations,
and that although July was traditionally a clearance month, they
sold more goods at full price.
</P>
<P>
The good performance was attributed partly to solid sales in
May and June, which helped clear out inventories, leaving
retailers more room to bring in new season and back-to-school
merchandise, which sold at regular price.
</P>
<P>
All of this is a good sign for retail earnings for the fiscal
second quarter which for most retailers ended in July.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter also saw positive earnings for many U.S.
retailers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
