<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Ending Olympic Deal Over Cost Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 7 (Xinhua)-- International Business Machines
Corp. is ending its worldwide sponsorship of the Olympic Games,
severing a 38-year marketing relationship in a wrangle over the
high cost of linking corporate marketing to sports, the Wall
Street Journal reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The pull-out came after several months of futile negotiations
with the International Olympic Committee, IBM said.
</P>
<P>
IBM wanted local organizing committees to start bearing some of
the technology costs. The two sides, however, could not agree on
how much money the local Olympic organizers should pay IBM and how
much IBM should have to give in exchange for marketing rights to
the Olympic rings, IBM said.
</P>
<P>
So the company is chose to walk away rather than lock up an
eight-year deal with the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
The world computer giant spent more than 100 million U.S.
dollars to sponsor the 1998 Winter Games and provided much of the
technology behind it free of charge.
</P>
<P>
The bailout by IBM means that its sponsorship of the next
Olympics, the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney, Australia, may be the
company's last.
</P>
<P>
IBM said that it was "fully committed to making the millennium
games an outstanding event" and "will market it heavily". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
