<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Danish Delegation Visits Tibetan Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A Danish parliamentary delegation
today visited the Tibet Autonomous Region Prison in the northern
subrubs of Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
The facility, one of only three prisons in Tibet, houses 800
prisoners, with Tibetans accounting for 75 percent of the total
and members of the Han nationality 20 percent. Eight percent of
the prisoners were convicted of crimes involving breaches of
national security. The facility also houses some eight percent of
convicted female prisoners in the region.
</P>
<P>
The warden told the Danish delegation that the prison's goal is
to rehabilitate prisoners through education and labor reform. The
prisoners work three days, study two days and rest two days each
week.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners are treated fairly and enjoy an annual allocations of
2,800 yuan (330 US dollars) each provided by the government, said
the warden, adding that the prisoners have improved their quality
of life by growing vegetables and raising poultry.
</P>
<P>
The Danish delegation also visited dormitories, a dining room
and the prison school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
