<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Starts Minting Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MUNICH, August 7 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo
Waigel Friday launched the minting of German-version euro coins at
the Bavarian General Mint in southern German city of Munich.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Waigel stressed again the significance of the
use of the euro in Europe, saying that the use of the single
European currency would remove the currency borders among European
Union (EU) countries, facilitating trade within Europe.
</P>
<P>
The European Monetary Union (EMU) was a great leap forward in
Europe's economic and political development, he added.
</P>
<P>
The euro is planned to be launched on January 1, 1999, in
European Union (EU) countries that join the EMU, which includes
Germany.
</P>
<P>
It is agreed that the euro will enter into circulation from
January 1, 2002, and must completely replace national currencies
of the EMU member countries by the end of June 30, 2002.
</P>
<P>
Bonn is considering shortening the euro transit period in
Germany in order to reduce the costs of switching over to another
currency from the German mark.
</P>
<P>
There are one-cent, two-cent, five-cent, 10-cent, 20-cent,
50-cent, one-euro and two-euro euro coins. Each category has a
unified front, and backs with different patterns bearing national
characteristics for easy acceptance by peoples. For Germany, the
back patterns are the German federal eagle, Brandenburg gate and
oak leaves.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Bavarian General Mint, the mints in Berlin,
Hamburg, Karlsruhe and Stuttgart are also authorized in Germany to
mint the euro.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 12.1 billion euro coins weighing 50,000 tons will
be needed in Germany alone when the euro completely enters into
circulation in EMU countries in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The specially-designed euro coins are highly
anti-counterfeiting, and can be easily distinguished by the blind
people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
