<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's 1st EPZ Abandoned by Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's first export processing
zone (EPZ), gulping a huge investment of 600 million U.S.
Dollars, has proved to be a failure, as political instability has
scared off investors.
</P>
<P>
The EPZ in Calabar, Cross Rivers State, in southeast Nigeria,
was established through Decree 63 of 1992. It was expected that
the EPZ would attract more investors to Nigeria and boost its
non-oil exports.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, the law establishing the EPZ provides a wide
range of incentives for export-oriented investment in the zone,
including tax incentives and leasing of factories by instalments
in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the construction of infrastructure
facilities in the EPZ, including water and power supply,
telecommunications, roads and standard factory plants has cost
the Nigerian government 50 billion Naira (about 600 million
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The dredging of the Calabar port alone, undertaken by a
Chinese firm, cost 50 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the authorities have approved 19 firms to operate
in EPZ, including two textile and garments manufacturers with
foreign investment and a local wood products firm had reportedly
started test running by 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, now that the facilities are 95 percent completed,
none of the 19 approved firms have actually started business,
even the said three firms have abandoned their projects.
</P>
<P>
A recent visit to the EPZ by some reporters proved that it has
been actually deserted. The facilities are getting submerged in
overgrown bushes, while some buildings even have their zinc roof
blown off in rain storms.
</P>
<P>
This explains why the formal commissioning of the EPZ has been
delayed again and again.
</P>
<P>
An official of the EPZ authority said: "we don't want to
commission the EPZ when there are no activities here. Sincerely
speaking, the problem has to do with patronage."
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that political instability and poor
infrastructure are the major obstacles preventing more foreign
investors from coming to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian newspaper recently quoted a western country's high
commission as warning its businesses to be cautious in investing
in Nigeria, saying it is better for them to be satisfied with
trade at the moment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
