<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Danish Delegation Meets Tibetan Economists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A Danish delegation visiting Tibet
participated in a Friday symposium with local economists.
</P>
<P>
Gou Ling, an economist with the Tibet Planning Committee,
briefed the delegation on social and economic development in Tibet
since peacefully liberation some 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Tibet's 1997 gross domestic product hit 7.6 billion yuan, with
the average annual income of farmers surpassing 1,008 yuan, and
the level for residents in cities and towns topping 5,030 yuan.
The region's total population stands at slightly over 2.42
million, compared to only one million in late 1950s. Tibetans
currently account for 95 percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has initially formed an industrial system based on
textiles, hydropower and leather processing. The region's 4,000
primary schools, secondary schools and universities have a total
enrollment of 320,000 students.
</P>
<P>
The economist pointed out that Tibet's target is to basically
realize modernization by the middle of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He added that Tibet has scored major achievements with
extensive support provided by the central government which has
invested some 12 billion yuan in infrastructure construction over
the past 40 years. Scores of key construction projects in Tibet
have resulted in significant changes and brought great benefits to
local residents.
</P>
<P>
The Danish delegation also inquired about issues such as
environmental protection, the self-autonomy of ethnic minorities,
education in the Tibetan language and family planning.
</P>
<P>
The Danish parliamentary delegation, headed by Foreign Affairs
Committee Chairperson Helle Degn, also visited the Potala Palace
and Johkang Temple today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
