<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Devaluates Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam on Friday effectively
devalued its currency, the dong, by about seven percent, bowing to
pressure resulting from the financial crisis that has ravaged
Southeast Asia since July last year.
</P>
<P>
On Friday morning, the State Bank of Vietnam lowered the
official rate of the dong to the dollar by 10 percent from 11,816
on Thursday to 12,998, while simultaneously narrowing the trading
band on either side of this rate from 10 to seven percent.
</P>
<P>
Because the dong traded at the ceiling of this trading band
before and after the devaluation, the effective devaluation
equalled seven percent.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Friday, the bank described the
devaluation as a necessary move aimed at forming a rational
exchange rate between the dong and the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The state bank's macro-control over the exchange rate would
encourage exports, limit imports and contribute to the increase of
the country's foreign exchange reserves, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The state bank has demanded all financial organizations
engaging foreign exchanges to set their rates in accordance with
the official one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
