<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-07 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Says Not to Yield on Missile Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said Friday that Cyprus would not yield to foreign
pressures over its planned deployment of Russian-made S-300
anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark during a meeting with a delegation of
refugees who had fled from areas in northern Cyprus, now under the
control of Turkish Cypriots, Cyprus News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said foreign officials have made suggestions on the
missile issue, and the Cypriot government has replied accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a 425-million-U.S.-dollar deal with Russia early
last year to buy the sophisticated surface-to-air missiles, which
are due to be delivered and deployed late this year.
</P>
<P>
This is seen as a threat by Turkish Cypriots in the north and
Turkey, which has threatened a pre-emptive strike if they are
deployed.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign governments, especially the U.S. and Britain, have
voiced opposition to Cyprus' plan.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Foreign Under-Secretary Yiannos Kranidiotis on
Friday briefed Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides on his
meeting in Athens early this week with United States Ambassador to
Greece Nicholas Burns on the missile issue.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides told reporters that the Greek diplomat's talks with
Burns were identical with those held recently between Cypriot
officials and U.S. Special Coordinator for Cyprus Thomas Miller.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to go into details of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Burns has reportedly proposed that Cyprus opt for the shorter
range S-15 missile system, instead of the S-300 system.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed a moratorium of Greek and Turkish military
overlight in Cyprus, which will be monitored by the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has made it clear that it is ready to cancel the missile
deal if peace talks between the two communities on the island make
substantial progress, or the proposed demilitarization of the
island is agreed on.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained more than 35,000 troops in northern
Cyprus, with the claimed aim to protect the Turkish Cypriot
minority.
</P>
<P>
The peace process toward a solution to the long-running Cyprus
issue broke down last summer after the Turkish Cypriots withdrawed
to protest against a European Union (EU) decision to start
accession talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots, who declared in 1983 a breakaway republic
in the north recognized only by Turkey, refused to join the
Cypriot government team in negotiations with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The international community has made efforts to help reunify
the island under the United Nations-sponsored bi-zonal and
bi-communal formula. But no tangible progress was achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Water Levels Continues to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Flood situation has been worsening
further in central China's Hubei Province on Friday night as water
levels of Yangtze River are expected to go further in the coming
hours, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
At 24:00 pm, water level at the Shashi Measuring Point,
upstream of Wuhan, the provincial capital, buoyed up to 44.92 m,
compared with 44.88 m at just two hours before.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Shashi has further approached the level for
a proposed diversion plan to discharge flood waters into the
Jingjiang diversion zone, in Gong'an County, about 200 kilometers
west of Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
Some 250,000 local residents in the zone have been evacuated to
make way for the diversion so far. A total of 330,000 people are
expected to be resettled from the diversion area.
</P>
<P>
In related developments, the year's fourth flood crest passed
Yichang, upstream of Shashi, and is expected to reach Shashi
between 8:00-10:00 am on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Shashi is doomed to top 45 m, an expert from
the Yangtze River Water Conservancy Committee said.
</P>
<P>
However, the expert declined to discuss whether there will be a
diversion in the Jingjiang diversion zone, only noting that there
are two preconditions for the materialization of the diversion
program. A water level of 45 m and above, and it is going up
further in a foreseeable period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
