<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts Continued to Plug Up Breach in Jiujiang Dykes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Seven boats have by far been
dumped into a 40-meter breach of the city defence embankments in
Jiujiang City, east China's Jiangxi Province, with more following.
</P>
<P>
Bags of rice, soybean, and stones were also used for the
effort. As a result, most of the raging floodwaters have been
blocked, however, there are still some sneaking out into the city
through gaps between the sunken boats.
</P>
<P>
Now, thousands of soldiers and civilians are working to plug up
the breach, using more boats and other materials. And another
1,700 armed police are rushing to reinforce the effort, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
At about 12:30 Friday, a water-sodden point was found at the
city defence dykes, and dozens of minutes later grew into a leak
of two feet, and at 4 pm, the city defense embankments partially
collapsed, and water two meters deep began to inundate western
parts of the city through a 40-meter breach.
</P>
<P>
A coal boat on the river was ordered to come, and sunken to
block it, with another two boats joining in. The three sunken
boats have considerably slowed floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
Locally stationed soldiers are busy building a second
barrier. Eight boatloads of stone and 2,000 tons of rice are being
dumped into the breach.
</P>
<P>
The local Flood Control Headquarters has urged residents to
evacuate the area. People were transporting valuables to high
land, and all shops have closed.
</P>
<P>
The provincial Party secretary and governor have hurried to the
scene to guide the rescue work, and efforts are being made to
build another two barriers to protect the rest of the city.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang City, along the southern bank of the middle reaches of
the Yangtze River, lies in the northern parts of east China's
Jiangxi Province, and the city proper covers an area of 42 square
kilometers, with a population of 500,000.
</P>
<P>
It has a lot of lakes and rivers, and the most well-known is
the Poyang Lake, the country's largest freshwater lake. For weeks,
the 3,976-square-kilometer lake has maintained record flooding
water levels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
