<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Carbomb Blasts at US Embassy in Tanzanian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- A powerful carbomb exploded
Friday morning at the entrance to the United States Embassy in the
Tanzanian capital, killing at least seven and injuring more than
50 Tanzanians.
</P>
<P>
The explosion happened at about 10:50 local time (0750 GMT) and
we felt a violent shake rocking the two-story building of the
Xinhua Bureau here like an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
We drove our Nissan Patrol out of the plot and saw sirening
ambulances in a row rushing toward the seaside residence district
for embassies, where a dense smoke can be seen rising against the
blue sky.
</P>
<P>
When we arrived at a three-story white building with a Stars
and Stripes flag waving on its top -- the Embassy of the United
States, a group of US marine soldiers, armed with automatic rifles
and wearing camouflage helmets and bullet-proof vests, began
posting a cordon together with the baton-waving Tanzanian
policemen.
</P>
<P>
Following the firemen, we managed to reach the center of the
blasting, where we saw several reception and guard rooms have been
leveled. The North-Eastern corner of the main building has fallen
into rubble, tongues of fire jumping around.
</P>
<P>
A dozen of cars and jeeps were left outside the cement bar of
the embassy, some of which are broken into pieces. Some vehicles
are burning, one with T116 (US Embassy) plate is still flashing
its emergency lights.
</P>
<P>
A car-sized and about 1.5 meter-deep pit can be seen clearly
among the damaged vehicles.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, this is the blasting center. It is a carbomb," a
Tanzanian police officer told us.
</P>
<P>
About 20 meters from the entrance, a bloody body without head
and a leg were seen on the grass. Farther away there lies a
broken hand, a bare right foot and several pieces of bleeding
flesh.
</P>
<P>
Many tall trees along the street outside the embassy were
broken in the middle part, leaving branches and dozens of green
papayas on the street.
</P>
<P>
The civilian houses surrounding the embassy also suffered
heavily. Some roofs were pulled off while others lost the walls,
leaking beds and chairs out.
</P>
<P>
The fire came under control finally when we were forced by the
plain clothed policemen to leave the site.
</P>
<P>
We droved at noon to the well-equipped Muhimbili Medical
Center where David Mwakyusa, spokesman for the hospital, told us
that 57 civilians, all Tanzanians, have so far been admitted and
six of them have died.
</P>
<P>
"An American, who was injured, refused the admission," he said.
</P>
<P>
When we left the hospital, an ambulance with a Red Cross flag
sirened in and was immediately surrounded by the Tanzanians who
wanted to identify whether their family members were inside.
</P>
<P>
A similar explosion has been reported attacking the US embassy
in Kenya's capital Nairobi almost at the same time, but on one has
claimed responsibility for the double attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
