<HEADLINE> Mkapa Pledges Stern Action on U.S. Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa Friday promised swift action to track down those
responsible for bombing U.S. embassies in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania
and Nairobi, Kenya in coordinated attacks.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who arrived in Zimbabwe's western resort of Victoria
Falls for a two-day emergency summit of seven eastern and
southern African leaders to discuss the rebellion in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), said his government was
working with the U.S. embassy in Dar es Salaam to track down the
perpetrators of the crime.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to unearth all this. We are going to cooperate
with the U.S. embassy staff on this and when we do we are going
to take very stern measures indeed," Mkapa told journalists at
Victoria Falls Airport, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Five people were killed in the bomb attack in Dar es Salaam
which went off only minutes after a similar explosion in Kenya,
in which 40 were killed.
</P>
<P>
Also to arrive for the crisis summit were Rwandan President
Pasteur Bizimungu who came on the same presidential flight with
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba from Lusaka where he was on
an official visit.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu, whose tiny country is blamed by its giant
neighbour, the DRC, of fomenting the Tutsi-led armed rebellion in
the east of the country, refused to answer questions from
journalists covering the summit.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma and host President Robert Mugabe
arrived earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Other leaders still to arrive on Friday evening were Uganda's
Yoweri Museveni, who broached the emergency summit idea to
discuss the worsening situation in the DRC, formerly Zaire,
Africa's third largest country.
</P>
<P>
DRC President Laurent Kabila, who came to power in May last
year after a seven-month Tutsi-led guerillar campaign, was
expected in Victoria Falls later in the evening. 
</P>
