<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legendary Man Saves Yangtze River Dyke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese love and respect a hero
and those feelings can be even stronger when the hero faces even
greater difficulties than other heroes.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhancheng, a man in his late 60s who is handicapped, was
recently given a 10,000 yuan award by the city government of
Wuhan, the capital of Hubei Province, for the bravery he displayed
in saving the Yangtze River dykes.
</P>
<P>
On July 30, Wang, who has decades of experience in fighting
floods, used his own body to block a one meter hole on the city's
embankment he saw. Wang joined several young people and succeeded
in plugging the hole with sandbags after standing waist-deep in
the water for an hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
The provincial flood-control headquarters said that Wang's
bravery had in fact saved the dyke from a potentially disastrous
breach that could have affected the entire industrial area.
</P>
<P>
Wang is a retired employee of a local petrochemical company and
a skillful swimmer. But, the important thing is, to some he's been
a hero for decades. Wang was wounded during the War to Resist US
Aggression and Aid Korea (1950-53) and suffered damage to his
legs, but, 1954, he won a government award for his work in pulling
people out of raging floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
"I've fought floods for decades," Wang says simply, "and I'm
familiar with the dyke here," and adds, "I'm walking around the
dyke often, and it makes me feel good just looking over the dyke
and the water." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
