<HEADLINE> No Deal on Palestinian-Israeli Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
officials had phone contacts over the weekend, but did not decide
whether to continue their so far fruitless direct peace talks.
</P>
<P>
A senior Palestinian source said Saturday it was not known if
the two sides would resume negotiations on Israel's troop
redeployment in the West Bank, a long-running hurdle for more than
a year.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides did contact with each other during the last two
days via telephone, but no agreement was reached on whether to
continue the peace talks," the source added.
</P>
<P>
Senior direct talks between the two sides were resumed on July
19 after a lapse of 16 months. The Israeli side has been insisting
on making changes in the U.S. initiative calling for a 13.1
percent Israeli pullback, but the Palestinian side rejected it.
</P>
<P>
Israel proposed to hand over 10 percent, and turn the other 3
percent into a "nature reserve" to limit Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side demanded Israel accept the U.S. initiative
and withdraw from another 13.1 percent of the West Bank in the
second stage redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, the Palestinian side said they will not continue
such direct talks with Israel because it has nothing to offer.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat said over the weekend
that it is up to Chairman Yasser Arafat to decide whether the
Palestinian side would continue the talks, but no official
statement was made so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
