<HEADLINE> Chinese Military's Emergency Rescue Efforts During Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Central Military Commission
issued emergency orders for 30,000 officers and enlisted men of
the PLA (People's Liberation Army) and armed police for
protecting Yangtze River dykes, which are threatened by the flood
peak.
</P>
<P>
According to sources with the Headquarters of the General
Staff, the Guangzhou Military Area Command has sent 34 aircraft to
Hubei Province since yesterday evening, because of reports of the
dangerous situation there. They carried emergency rescue teams and
flood-relief materials to take on the worst flooding this decade.
</P>
<P>
For the past several days, the command headquarters has sent
over 2,000 tons of life preservers, medicines, and food to the
flooding-stricken provinces by air.
</P>
<P>
Over 7,000 soldiers from the Jinan Military Area Command formed
emergency units in Hubei Province and have rescued more than
20,000 people caught by the floodwaters and helped to reinforce
6,000 meters of dikes.
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing Military Area Command sent 7,200 soldiers to
Jiujiang in Jiangxi Province to repair dikes and to work
round-the-clock rescuing people.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 100,000 military personnel have been sent to
flood-ravaged provinces in central and eastern parts of China to
join local militiamen in the fight against heavy flooding and to
provide emergency relief.  
</P>
</TEXT>
