<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese And Japanese Foreign Ministers' Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan, in a meeting here today with his Japanese counterpart
Masahiko Komura for talks on bilateral relations and regional and
global issues, said that Sino-Japanese ties are good in general
and that bilateral cooperation is moving forward.
</P>
<P>
Some problems can not be neglected, Tang said, and China
expects Japan to observe all principles on the Taiwan issue and to
be cautious in guarding Sino-Japanese ties.
</P>
<P>
This year is the 20th anniversary of the signing of the
Sino-Japanese Peace and Friendly Treaty, he said, and bilateral
relations are at a pivotal and important historic point.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin is scheduled to visit Japan this fall, he
pointed out, and this historic visit comes at the end of the
century and is expected to summerize both the positive and
negative experiences of Sino-Japanese ties and provide a blueprint
for long-term bilateral friendly and cooperative ties for the 21st
century. He also hopes that the two sides will step up
preparations to ensure Jiang's coming visit a success.
</P>
<P>
Komura expressed his sympathy for the serious flood problems in
central China and announced that there would be new aid for
China's disaster-stricken areas. He said that the new Japanese
cabinet places importance on relations with China and that his
visit to China not long after the new government was formed is a
sign of this.
</P>
<P>
He said that Jiang's visit will be the first paid by the head
of state of China and an important event in bilateral ties. He
said he believes it will lay a sound foundation for friendly ties
between the two countries and make new contribution to regional
and international peace and development.
</P>
<P>
He said he appreciates the efforts of the Chinese government
to keep its currency stable while increasing domestic reforms even
during this period of financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Tang said that China's stand is consistent and he
asked Japan's new government to take steps to improve domestic
economic stability and make a contribution to regional economic
revival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
