<HEADLINE> One Chinese County Offers To Destroy Dykes To Save Major City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- While the county of Gong'an was
busy preparing a possible flood diversion scheme that could save
the city of Wuhan, the capital of China's Hubei Province, another
county offered to blow up its dykes for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
The Jingjiang Flood Diversion Zone in Gong'an, 200 km upstream
from Wuhan, is set to be the first stage of a proposed diversion
program to discharge floodwater from the Yangtze River, and some
residents of Jingjiang were being evacuated to make way for the
diversion on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
So, the leaders of Jianli County, 150 km upstream from
Wuhan, volunteered their area as another site for a diversion to
share Gong'an's woes.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation in Hubei has not gotten much better, even
though the water level at the Shashi measuring point, 200 km
upstream from Wuhan, has been receding gradually. The water level
there fell to 44.8 m. at 6:00 p.m. Saturday and it is likely to
fall further in the coming hours, according to local hydrometric
departments, but the authorities are still considering the
diversion scheme for the safety of Wuhan, says one source.
</P>
<P>
The diversion would be carried out when the water level at
Shashi reaches 45 m. and is still going up. It would mean that a
part of Yangtze's embankments in Gong'an would be dynamited and
the North Flood Gate would be opened to discharge
floodwater. 
</P>
</TEXT>
