<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Committee Set Up to Probe Conflict in Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Seven African leaders Saturday
decided to set up a four-member committee from among themselves
to immediately seek an end to the armed rebellion in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Addressing journalists at the end of the six-hour meeting in
Zimbabwe's western resort town of Victoria Falls, host President
Robert Mugabe said a committee of four summit participants had
been formed to immediately start work to ensure that fighting
stopped in the DRC where a Tutsi-inspired rebellion has been
raging since last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The committee comprises Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa,
Zambian President Fredrick Chiluba, Namibian President Sam Nujoma
and Mugabe as its chairman, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting to tackle the escalating conflict in the Great
Lakes region was sponsored by Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
and was chaired by Mugabe, with Chiluba, Mkapa, Nujoma, DRC
President Laurent Kabila and Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu
attending.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the meeting deliberated on the situation in the
Great Lakes region especially as it affected relations between
the DRC and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
He said the DRC was blaming Rwanda of inspiring fighting in
certain areas of the vast central African country especially the
eastern parts.
</P>
<P>
"The DRC has blamed Bwanda for invading its territory and some
groups have taken over some of the border towns," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
But he added Rwanda on the contrary denied any involvement and
alleged that the conflict was an internal one brought about by
dissension and differences within the country.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said that the committee's first priority would be to
see that fighting stopped immediately.
</P>
<P>
He said they would establish who was fighting in the DRC,
whether they were Rwandan troops as alleged or the DRC army
rebels and whoever was doing the fighting should stop
immediately.
</P>
<P>
"We want the fighting to stop and therefore revert to
normalcy. It should go back to a situation of peace and peaceful
neighborliness," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean president also said the leaders had condemned
in strongest terms the bombing that took place almost
simultaneously in Kenyan capital Nairobi and Tanzanian capital
Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said Africa would not stand by and allow its people to
be killed and whoever had perpetrated the act would be deemed as
an enemy of Africa and the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
The leaders are expected to leave for their respective
countries after the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Situation Getting Worse In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The flood situation in China's
Hunan Province got worse on Saturday as the water level in
Dongting Lake rose quickly to an all-time high, according to local
officials.
</P>
<P>
At 6:00 pm today, the water level at Chenglingji, where the
lake joins the Yangtze River, was 35.5 m., 0.24 m. above the
previous record.
</P>
<P>
As the year's fourth flood crest continues to move downstream
in the direction of Hunan, the water level is expected to rise
further.
</P>
<P>
Governor Yang Zhengwu told Xinhua that the local dykes have
been weakened by a month-long assault by the high water and the
situation could turn perilous at any time.
</P>
<P>
The province's battle with the flood has entered a crucial
stage, he said, and there are more than 2 million people,
including thousands of soldiers and armed police, involved in it.
</P>
<P>
Local people have been told by the government that they need to
keep up the struggle to guard the embankments of the Yangtze and
Dongting Lake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
