<HEADLINE> Floods Cost Central Chinese Province 30 Billion Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rains and the worst
flooding since 1954 have cost China's Hubei province nearly 30
billion yuan (3.6 billion U.S. dollars) so far this year, official
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Some 61 counties, out of the total of 69, have been hit by the
disaster, and 1.65 million ha. of crops affected, according to the
provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that over 1.6 million people have had to be
evacuated to safer places. Local civil affairs departments began a
campaign today to solicit donations for the victims.
</P>
<P>
More than 21 million yuan was raised at the opening ceremony
here today, local official said, and they have received donations
from overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Banks Raise Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean commercial banks have
started to increase lending rates following the hike in the
rediscount rate by the Reserve Bank this week to shore up the
Zimbabwean Dollar which took a knock against major currencies.
</P>
<P>
Three banks have increased their rates by a minimum of three
percentage points following the raising of the rediscount rate by
the central bank from 31.5 percent to 35 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
The rediscount rate is the rate at which banks borrow money
from the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The Commercial Bank of Zimbabwe increased its interest rates
on all loans and overdrafts by 3.5 percent per annum while the
bank's minimum lending rate moved up from 35 percent to 38.5
percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
"This review is a result of recent market trends which saw the
upward revision of the rediscount rate," the bank said in a
statement Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Two other banks, First Bank and Stanbic Zimbabwe also raised
their prime lending rates to 38.5 percent and 38 percent per
annum respectively.
</P>
<P>
"Our credit interest rates will also be adjusted upwards with
effect from August 7, 1998," Stanbic said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The reserve bank hiked the rediscount rate in a bid to
stabilize the Zimbabwean Dollar which fell by about 12 percent
Monday under heavy speculative pressure from importers.
</P>
<P>
However, the pressure has since subsided and the Zimbabwean
Dollar closed the week stable trading at between 21 and 22
Zimbabwean Dollars to one U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
But the raising of the rediscount rate has the effect of
making borrowings from banks by businesses and individuals
expensive as they also raise their lending rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kunming Trade Fair Opens Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Kunming Trade Fair, which is
oriented towards Southeast Asia, opened today in the capital of
China's Yunnan Province, with 1,780 domestic and foreign
exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
The eight-day fair is expected to outperform previous fairs in
spite of the effects of the Asian financial crisis, according to
Shao Qiwei, vice-governor of the province.
</P>
<P>
He says that there will be business talks on tobacco,
machinery, clothing and electronics, and foreign investment will
be sought for highway and electric power projects.
</P>
<P>
The fair is sponsored by the city of Chongqing, the provinces
of Sichuan, Yunnan, and Guizhou, the Guangxi Zhuang and Tibet
autonomous regions, and Chengdu, the capital of Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
The first fair was held in 1993. It has done more than 7
billion U.S. dollars worth of business in the past five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
