<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Foreign Ministry Officials Discuss Afghan Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 8 (Xinhua) -- High-ranking officials from
Pakistan's Foreign Ministry held emergent consultations Saturday
on the latest Afghan situation after the Taliban militia marched
into the opposition stronghold of Mazar-i-Sharif, official sources
said.
</P>
<P>
No official word was available about the outcome of the
meeting. However, the sources said that Pakistan reiterated
that it will stick to its policy towards the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was the first country to have recognized the Taliban
government when they briefly entered Mazar-i-Sharif, the strategic
northern Afghan town in May 1997 after they struck a deal with
opposition commander General Abdul Malik.
</P>
<P>
However, the ethnic Hazara flushed the Taliban militia out of
the northern town killing hundreds of Taliban soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban Saturday claimed to have overrun the opposition
stronghold of Mazar-i-Sharif, the only major Afghan town which was
beyond the Taliban's control, after three hours of fierce fighting
with the rival Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The chief representative of the Taliban based in Islamabad,
Abdul Hakeem Mujahid, said that the Taliban leadership in the
southern town of Kandahar has confirmed the fall of the town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
