<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Condemns African Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon on Saturday strongly
condemned the terrorist bombings next to the United States'
embassies in the two African countries of Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
In a telegram sent to U.S. President Bill Clinton, Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi said that terrorism will never obstruct the
U.S. from continuing its fresh efforts in a bid to achieve peace
and stability in the world.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, two bombs blasted with minutes of each other in
Nairobi, Kenya and Dar-es-Salaam, Tanzania, apparently targeting
the U.S. embassies.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 have died, eight of them Americans, and over
1,000 injuried in the two bombings. Clinton has vowed to "use all
the means at our disposal to bring those responsible to justice,
no matter what or how long it takes."
</P>
<P>
During the day, Hrawi also sent messages to his Kenyan and
Tanzania counterparts Daniel arap Moi and Benjamin William Mkapa
to express condolence.
</P>
<P>
He denounced the bombings as a coward terrorist act and thus
unjustifiable.
</P>
<P>
He added that the act is intended against not only
U.S. interests but also international human rights and stability.
</P>
<P>
Less than two months ago a similar bomb blast occurred near the
U.S. embassy in Beirut in which no casualties were caused. But the
case is still under investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
