<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty to Hit 40 Percent of Indonesians: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Poverty is expected to hit 40
percent of Indonesia's more than 200 million population this year,
a senior minister said.
</P>
<P>
The figure is up from only 11.4 percent in 1996, Coordinating
Minister for People's Welfare and Poverty Eradication Haryono
Suyono said while opening a national meeting on total reforms in
Medan, North Sumatra, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Poverty has already hit some 11.4 million families across the
country, Antara News Agency quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the main cause of the increase of poverty was the
monetary crisis which has lasted for more than one year.
</P>
<P>
The crisis, which was described as the worst in the past 30
years, has made people lose confidence in government leaders and
institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
In facing the crisis, he said, people should again participate
and encourage others to participate in development efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has expected the economy to contract
by 15 percent this year, but it was optimistic that the country
will record a positive growth in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry
Ginandjar Kartasamita said earlier the country's inflation, which
is estimated to reach 80 percent this year, is expected to fall
into single digit by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
