<HEADLINE> Congolese FM Ends Visit to Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister of the Republic of
Congo Rodolphe Adada left here for home Saturday after wrapping up
a three-day visit to Egypt, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, who saw him off at the
airport, told reporters that Adada conveyed a message to President
Hosni Mubarak from Congolese President Denis Sassou-Nguess. But he
did not disclose its content.
</P>
<P>
The message was delivered by Adada to his Egyptian counterpart
at a meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting Adada briefed Moussa on the situation in his
country and the impact of the civil war that ripped through the
neighboring Democratic Congo (formerly Zaire).
</P>
<P>
The talks also handled the situation in the Horn of Africa,
Sudan, the Great Lakes as well as the Middle East, Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to set up a joint agricultural
project in the Western African republic with the help of Egyptian
expertise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
