<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore PM  Calls for Unity to Meet Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong Saturday called upon the whole nation to rally together
and meet the most formidable challenges since independence in
1965.
</P>
<P>
In a national day message to mark the country's 33rd
independence anniversary which falls on August 9, Goh Chok Tong
said, "Let us rally together and meet the challenge head-on.
United we will prevail, and emerge stronger than before."
</P>
<P>
While giving a bleak picture about the regional situation, Goh
Said the regional crisis is a challenge to all Singaporeans and in
economic terms the problems the country is facing are more serious
than the oil-shock of 1973, or the recession in 1985 in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
According to the prime minister, Singapore's economic growth
fell to 1.6 percent in the second quarter from the same period
last year, the Singapore dollar has depreciated by some 20 percent
against the U.S. dollar, external demand for Singapore-made goods
and services has dropped sharply, and some companies have had to
retrench workers.
</P>
<P>
Go Chok Tong said that for the first time in many years the
country's budget will be in deficit this year and there will be
another budget deficit next year.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has taken a series of moves including
measures to reduce business costs, to attract investments, and to
train and retrain everyone to his full potential.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the task facing the country to competing in the World
Cup that ended in France about a month ago, the prime minister
stressed "the key to our long-term competitiveness is first the
collective skills of our people, and the next how well we
organize ourselves." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
