<HEADLINE> Bombing Casualties Exceed 4,200 in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- One hundred and eight people
were killed and 4,149 others injured in Friday's car bombing near
the U.S. embassy in Nairobi's downtown area, Kenyan Foreign
Minister Bonaya Godana said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with foreign envoys here, the minister said that
most of the injured have been given out-patient treatment while
over 500 wounded have been admitted at major hospitals in the
capital and 24 serious cases in the intensive care units.
</P>
<P>
There are still one man and one woman who are believed to be
alive under the rubble and the rescue workers are trying hard to
get them out.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorism has been brought to our doosteps," Godana noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi also said that his
country was not at war with any country and, therefore, Kenya
should not be destroyed by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Kenyans are peaceful and did not
deserve such wanton destruction.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation agents and medical
experts arrived in Nairobi Saturday morning and have begun probe
into the bomb attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
