<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Elevated Railway Gets Bank of Communications Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- China's first elevated railway,
which will be built in the city of Shanghai, received a
1.2-billion-yuan (145 million U.S. dollars) loan from the Bank of
Communications today.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Wei, a deputy-president of the bank, says that it pays a
great deal of attention to key infrastructure construction
projects and supports them.
</P>
<P>
The 25-kilometer railway line has been approved by the State
Council and will be the city's largest traffic project for this
century. Its cost is estimated at 8.5 billion yuan. It is expected
to be completed by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, Shanghai has set up a company
to oversee the project, which has spent about 3 billion yuan and
is seeking loans from foreign governments to finance the remainder
of the construction work.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Communications provided 33 billion yuan in loans
last year for the city's economic and civil construction
projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
