<HEADLINE> Taliban Storms into Opposition Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
launched a major attack on Mazar-i-Sharif, the stronghold of the
anti-Taliban Northern Alliance Saturday morning, and stormed into
the city after breaking through the opposition defenses.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Hakeem Mujahid, chief representative of the Taliban
militia based in Islamabad, told Xinhua that he had received
reports that the Taliban had taken full control of Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Taliban sources from Mazar-i-Sharif also said that their forces
had secured full control over the dusty opposition bastion.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that a total of 5,000 Taliban troops took part
in Saturday's fighting which started from Daulatabad area, about
40 kilometers north of the city. The Taliban entered the city
after mid-day following hours of intense fighting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to media reports reaching here from
Mazar-i-Sharif Saturday afternoon, the bulk of opposition forces
were fleeing south to the mountainous central Massif of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Iranian News Agency, IRNA, said that
Mazar-i-Sharif, the only major Afghan city which was beyond the
Taliban's control, has been totally over-run by the Taliban
militia.
</P>
<P>
"The city fell moments ago and repeated explosions are being
heard in the city," IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
"There are only pockets of resistance, alliance officials have
left the town and people too are fleeing," it said, adding that
"parts of Mazar-i-Sharif are now burning and many homes have been
destroyed."
</P>
<P>
Taliban sources said that they used jet planes, conducting air
raids against the military targets of the Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Relief agencies have already withdrawn from the city in fear of
 fighting after the Taliban captured Shiberghan, capital of
Jawzjan province last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time that the Taliban has entered
Mazar-i-Sharif. The Taliban seized control of the city in May 1997
after joining ranks with Abdul Malik, a former ally of opposition
warlord Abdul Rashid Dostam, who allowed them to enter the
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
However, when a deal over power sharing broke down, Malik
returned to the fold of the anti-Taliban Northern Alliance to
inflict a brutal killing on at least 2,500 Taliban soldiers
trapped in the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
