<HEADLINE> Jordan Hopes Iran, U.S. to Improve Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Deputy Prime
Minister for Development Jawad Anani has said Jordan hopes
relations between Iran and the United States will be improved
through direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Anani, who is also foreign minister and is due in Tehran later
Saturday for a visit, made the remark in an interview with the
Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Rai Al-Aam published Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said Amman was in favor of a rapprochement between Iran and
the United States as it would eventually affect positively the
relations between Iran and Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief that Washington and Tehran could
establish mutual understanding through direct dialog.
</P>
<P>
But Anani hinted that Washington should abandon the containment
strategy in its dealings with Iran.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed during the interview that his scheduled talks
with Iranian officials would deal with the issue of possessing
mass-destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
Jordan does not want Iran to be target of accusations
concerning the development of weapons of mass-destruction while
Israel claims the right to do so, Anani said. "We do not want
Israel to continue the development of mass-destruction arms," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said it was in the interest of his country and other Arab
states to hear the opinion of the Iranian leaders about the
possession of these weapons.
</P>
<P>
Anani's visit to Iran will be the first by a high ranking
Jordanian official since last year, when Jordan's Crown Prince
Hassan Ibn Talal traveled to Tehran to attend the summit of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC). 
</P>
