<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is expected to send an
amphibious division and war planes on Wednesday to take part in
military exercises of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO).
</P>
<P>
Turkish newspaper Daily News reported Saturday that Turkey will
also send four F-16 fighters, a transport plane, a frigate and
other logistic support to participate in the Cooperative
Assembly-'98 exercises between August 17 and 22.
</P>
<P>
The manoeuvres will be carried out in Albanian and Macedonian
territories and are based on a scenario to end regional conflicts
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Eleven NATO countries, namely, Belgium, Canada, France,
Germany, Greece, Italy, the Netherlands, Spain, Turkey, the United
States and Britain, and three members of the Partnership for Peace
(PfP) program, namely, Albania, Lithuania and Russia, will take
part in the exercises. Eight other PfP countries will also take
part as observers.
</P>
<P>
The land, air and naval forces of the participating countries
will be involved in search-and-rescue missions and medical
evacuations. 
