<HEADLINE> Fourth Flood Crest Passes Through Central Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The fourth flood crest on the
Yangtze River passed through the city of Yichang in Hubei Province
early this morning.
</P>
<P>
The city's 267 km of embankments remained intact, according to
reports today.
</P>
<P>
Because of torrential rains on the river's upper reaches, the
river was flowing at 61,500 cu.m. per second when the peak
approached Yichang around 10:00 p.m. yesterday.
</P>
<P>
An hour later, the crest joined water from the Qingjiang River
and headed downstream at an even bigger rate of flow, raising the
water level of the river below Yichang to above the danger mark.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the safety of the dykes, especially on the Jingjiang
section, the secretary of the Yichang City Communist Party
Committee, Tian Zhenya, and the city's Mayor Sun Zhigang got
thousands of government employees and 40,000 residents and
soldiers to work on the embankments through the night.
</P>
<P>
After a 24-hour fight, they managed to stop several cave-ins
along the embankment before the fourth flood crest hit.
</P>
<P>
Water levels at Yichang went down slowly today, and by 5:00
p.m. today, they were down to 53.21 m., down 0.7 m. from the
highest level, and the flow rate was down to 56,600 cu.m. per
second, down 4,900 cu.m. from the highest rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
