<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Financial Secretary
Donald Tsang departed here Saturday for Istanbul for a three-day
visit to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Turkey, Tsang will meet with the Minister of
State in charge of Turkish Central Bank and Foreign Economic
Relations Gunes Taner. He will speak at a lunch hosted by the Hong
Kong Trade Development Council which will be attended by key
business leaders, and visit the Stock Exchange, according to the
Hong Kong Government Information Services.
</P>
<P>
Tsang will update his Turkish counterparts on the business
environment in Hong Kong and will highlight the ample
opportunities available. The official will also promote Hong Kong
on the tourism front.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the value of visible trade between
Hong Kong and Turkey grew by an average of 24 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Hong Kong is a major conduit for indirect trade
between Turkey and the Chinese mainland, which amounted to 3.4
billion HK dollars (436 million U.S. dollars) in 1997,
representing 71 percent of the Sino-Turkish trade. This
particular stream of re-exports through Hong Kong has witnessed a
fast growth, averaging at 21 percent per annum over the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had announced last month visa-free access for a period
up to three months for holders of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region passports. 
</P>
