<HEADLINE> Tanzania Vows to Track Terrorists in US Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice-President
Omar Ali Juma said Saturday morning that his country will
cooperate with the United States in tracking those who are
responsible for the bombing of the U.S. embassy in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president made the remarks during a tour to the
embassy which was wrecked by a horrifying bomb at about 10:45
a.m. Friday which left at least seven people dead and more than
70 others injured.
</P>
<P>
An initial investigation by the Tanzanian police showed that
the bomb was planted on an oil tanker belonging to the embassy.
</P>
<P>
Traffic around the heavily-guarded embassy compound has come
back to normal. The atmosphere is still tense with Tanzanian
policemen and soldiers standing on alert outside the embassy.
</P>
<P>
It is not immediately known whether the U.S. special
investigation team has arrived or not.
</P>
<P>
Several patients admitted into the Muhimbili Medical Center
have been transferred to private hospitals, medical sources said.
</P>
<P>
Simeon Ileta, spokesman for the Ministry of Foreign Affairs
and International Cooperation, said a statement will come out
later on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports reaching here said President Benjamin Mkapa
has condemned the bomb explosion.
</P>
<P>
It was "horrible and despicable," the president said Friday in
northern Zimbabwe, where he was joining six other African leaders
for a summit on the crisis concerning the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to try to unearth who is behind this... When we
do, we are going to take stern measures indeed," said Mpaka.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state-owned paper Daily News said that Prime
Minister Frederick Sumaye has categorically dissociated the event
with the relationship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"I assure the American friends that Tanzania values the
existing good relations between the two nations and would work
out toward consolidating the ties," he said at the National
Assembly Friday in the central city of Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye assured that the Tanzanian government will thoroughly
investigate into the incident and take actions against the
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye said the bombing, which occurred almost simultaneously
with another one near the U.S. embassy in Kenyan capital Nairobi,
was "a work of foreign hired mercenaries."
</P>
<P>
The premier on behalf of the entire government paid tribute to
all victims of the incident which has been the first of its kind
in the country.
</P>
<P>
He asked the National Assembly to condemn at their full length
the incident and called on people to remain calm as the state is
doing everything to establish its cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
