<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Sugar Plants to Be Transferred to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has agreed to transfer
its two biggest sugar plants to Mauritian Societe-Marromeu
consortium.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed in central city of Beira
Friday by Mozambican Minister of Agriculture and Fishery Carlos
do Rosario and his Mauritian counterpart, the Marromeu and Luabo
sugar plants in central Sofala Province, the two largest ones in
the southern African country, will be transferred to the
Mauritians.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Rosario said that the parent
company of the two sugar plants, Sena Sugar States will be
formally transferred to Societe-Marromeu, opening a broad future
for the development of the Zambeze Valley.
</P>
<P>
The transfer will restart the sugar manufacturing in central
Mozambique, the Mozambican said, adding that it will also boost
the development of animal raising and rice growing.
</P>
<P>
Rosario called on Mauritian investors to comply with their
commitments as written in the agreement and to solve various
problems through dialog.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the workers in the sugar plants to exert their
efforts to restore production.
</P>
<P>
The two sugar plants have been out of use since 1986 when war
broke out in the poor country.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican minister said that his government is trying to
rehabilitate all the sugar plants damaged by the war and to
ensure that the country can sustain without sugar imports with
its own sugar output reaching 310,000 tons by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Mozambique has to import some 120,000 tons of sugar
each year and it produces only 35,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Mauritian Minister of Agriculture, Fishery and Cooperation
Alvin Boolell pledged that his government will invest more into
the sugar industry in Mozambique, saying that this is beneficial
to both nations.
</P>
<P>
The transferred sugar plant, renamed as Compannia de Sena,
SARL, needs an investment of 70 million U.S. Dollars. It will
begin to produce sugar by the year of 2001, creating 5,000 jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
