<HEADLINE> China on DPP Attempt to Undermine Cross-Strait Relations (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The pompous allegation some
members of Taiwan's Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) have voiced
concerning the death of Lin Ti-chuan have mislead people on the
island province and sabotaged cross-straits relations, according
to a Xinhua commentator's article released today.
</P>
<P>
The commentator's article points to the DPP's irresponsible
remarks on Lin's case, and specifically rebukes the Taiwan party's
successive attacks concerning security and social stability on the
mainland, as well as its totally-misguided comments concerning the
mainland's indifference over the life and property of compatriots
from the island province, and the issue of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The DPP has pledged to press Taiwan authorities to suspend
cross-straits exchanges and require Koo Chen-fu, president of the
Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF), to cancel his anticipated visit
to the mainland in September, according to the commentary.
</P>
<P>
The article notes that the DPP enaged in repeated attempts to
send personnel to the Chinese mainland along with Lin's family.
</P>
<P>
DPP members have failed to comfort and assist the Lin's family,
and instead attempted to act as "the family's negotiators with the
Communist Party of China," meanwhile attempting to disrupt their
direct negotiations with concerned departments, says the
article. It goes on to acknowledge that the DPP's sole purpose is
to sway public opinions and create the illusion that "the Chinese
government failed to respect the will of Lin's family" and
instigate an emotional response from Taiwan compatriots.
</P>
<P>
The DPP urged the Taiwan law enforcement department and SEF
personnel to visit the scene of tragedy "to help conduct both
preliminary and follow-up investigations involving the case," so
as to prompt what the Taiwan party termed "diplomatic functions
between the two countries" and so-called "consular assistance".
</P>
</TEXT>
