<HEADLINE> Chittagong to Be Turned to Industrial, Commercial Hub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Chittagong Development
Authority (CDA) of Bangladesh has undertaken a five-year master
plan (1998-2002) to implement 34 projects with a view to turning
the city into an industrial and commercial hub.
</P>
<P>
All the projects with an estimated cost of 4.74 billion taka
(about 100.9 million U.S. dollars) included construction and
widening of five roads and development of four housing projects,
said media reports Saturday quoting CDA Chairman M. Zakaria as
saying recently.
</P>
<P>
The master plan was prepared in 1995 by the UNDP (United
Nations Development Program) in collaboration with the UNCHS
(United Nations Center for Human Settlements) and reviewed by a
12-member multi-sectoral experts under the guidelines issued by
the city mayor.
</P>
<P>
On the potentialities of Chittagong in the fields of economic
development, the CDA chief said that basic infrastructure
development and creation of congenial atmosphere was imperative to
attract foreign and local investment, the CDA chief stressed.
</P>
<P>
He underscored the importance of better coordination between
all agencies and public utility-service organizations for building
up the Chittagong city in a planned and pragmatic way.
</P>
<P>
Chittagong, 224 kilometers southeast of Dhaka, is the second
largest city and the biggest sea-port in South Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
