<HEADLINE> Zambia's ZCCM Mines Sale Terms Under Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
appointed a committee to improve the conditions which have been
set out earlier for the sale of its Zambia Consolidated Copper
Mines (ZCCM).
</P>
<P>
The committee is expected to draw up a plan that will speed up
the sale of the remaining ZCCM assets, notably Nchanga and Nkana
mines, which register 65 percent of Zambia's copper output,
Zambia Daily Mail reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The plan will be submitted to the ZCCM board of directors
within 14 days and later be forwarded to the government for final
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
The monentum in the sale of the assets has been slowed down by
breakdown of the negotiations in the past months which have
sometimes left the conglomerate's future uncertain.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Mines Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye as
saying in Lusaka Friday that the committee's main task will be to
draw up an action plan that would entice ZCCM buyers worldwide
and look at ways of marketing the mines internationally.
</P>
<P>
He also said that even in biddership, there should be ways to
keep the mines viable so that they continue generating funds on
the internaitonal market.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government is interested in speeding the mines's
privatisation process and wants ZCCM to clear the local and
foreign suppliers it owes money, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Zambian government with 60.3 percent shares
of the copper mines would like a successful completion of the
privatisation process, which is a precondition set for the
country to get 530 million U.S. Dollars pledged by western donors
last May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
