<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Part of Jiujiang City Submerged by Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Some four sq km of urban
Jiujiang, in east China's Jiangxi Province, has been submerged by
floodwater gushing in from a breach of the city's flood defense
embankment, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The city proper of Jiujiang, an industrial center and tourist
attraction located in the middle reaches of the Yangtze with an
urban population of about 500,000, has an area of about 30 sq km.
</P>
<P>
A 40-m-long breach occured Friday afternoon on the dike as
floods kept surging in the Yangtze River. But due to a mechanical
mishap in the process of refitting the embankment caused by a
power cut and to inadequate supply of filling materials like
rocks, stone and sand, the breach widened to 60 meters this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Currently, efforts are being intensified to re-settle affected
residents. Governor Shu Shengyou said that there were no reported
casualties yet in the breach by this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The situation caused by the breach is expected to be brought
under control this evening," Shu told Xinhua, noting that life has
been by and large normal in urban Jiujiang.
</P>
<P>
So far, supplies of running water, electricity and daily
necessities have been adequate as usual in the city.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of local residents, along with soldiers, have been
working hard to plug up the breach for the past 30 hours,
including sinking eight boats loaded with rock, as well as
thousands of tons of rice, coal, soybeans, into the breached
section.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
