<HEADLINE> Malaysian Countrymen Suggested to Pawn Valuables </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Saturday suggested that Malaysians pawn their
valuables such as jewelry abroad and use the money to help raise
more domestic capital resources for economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir made the suggestion when opening the 52nd general
assembly of the Malaysian Indian Congress (MIC) in Petaling Jaya
near here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The MIC, one of the 14 members of the ruling Barisan Nasional
(BN) (National Front) of which he is also the chairman, is the
BN's third largest component, representing the Indian community in
the country which accounts for some 8 percent of Malaysia's
population of about 21 million.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that there is hidden wealth worth billions of
dollars in the country," Mahathir said, adding by suggesting so,
he was not asking Malaysians to make outright national
contributions but only pawn their valuables overseas for cash as
an interim measure pending Malaysia's recovery from the current
economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"We want to increase our capital. This is one way of helping
the country without losing anything for yourself," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said "When our economy gets better, we can bring back the
jewelry from overseas."
</P>
<P>
The funds derived by pawning the valuables could be used in
efforts towards dealing with the economic downturn, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said by pawning their jewelry and other valuables,
Malaysians would display high patriotism in helping overcome the
country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the government would work very hard to improve
the economy so that those who have pawned their valuables overseas
could redeem them.
</P>
<P>
The one-day MIC assembly, attended by 1,350 delegates, was
expected to deliberate on efforts towards national economic
recovery and galvanizing teamwork among the Indian community to
join the government towards that end.
</P>
<P>
MIC President Samy Vellu, who is also Works Minister, called on
Malaysians to bolster solid support for Mahathir's stewardship of
the country in dealing with the current economic problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
