<HEADLINE> Saddam Calls on Iran to Sink Feud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on
Saturday called on Iran to sink a feud with Iraq and start
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He made the call in his nationally broadcast speech on the 10th
anniversary of the ending of the 8-year Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
"If some quarters in Iran abandoned what was not praiseworthy
of the past, they would see and find that the Arabs, including
Iraq, had abandoned this and left it long time ago," said the
Iraqi president.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that Iran "will also find every righteous,
beneficial cooperation from the Arabs, first and foremost, Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Saddam also called on Iran not to become a tool in the hand of
foreigner to harm Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The Arabs, including Iraqis, hope and call upon the officials
and peoples of Iraq not to become a tool in the hands of the
covetous foreigner to harm Arabs, primarily Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
Between 1980-1988, Iran and Iraq fought a bitter war due to
border disputes, leaving 1 million of people dead or wounded.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the two countries have stepped up efforts to solve
outstanding issues that have been standing in the way to the
normalization of relations.
</P>
<P>
In April, they repatriated some 6,000 of prisoners of war
(POWs) and detainees and promised to solve this issue of POWs
completely in the near future.
</P>
<P>
In June, they sent people to each other's territories to
search for those missing in action (MIA). 
</P>
</TEXT>
