<HEADLINE> Death Toll from Nairobi Bomb Blast Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
said the confirmed death toll from bomb blast at the U.S. embassy
in downtown Nairobi has reached 83 with a further 2,140 people
injured.
</P>
<P>
"As of this morning, 83 people have been confirmed dead, 497
have been admitted to various hospitals while 1,543 have been
treated and discharged," Moi said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Some people are still trapped under the debris of the
collapsed Ufundi (-Cooperative) building and efforts are being
made to rescue them," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
However, resue workers on the scene said the death toll will
still rise sharply and exceed 100.
</P>
<P>
A man trapped in the debris was found dead around 10:00 a.m.
Saturday. At least another was believed to be still alive under
the rubble but the rescue team has not found the person's exact
position.
</P>
<P>
International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) spokeswoman Nina
Golbe told Xinhua Saturday morning that another six bodies of
people were found overnight from the rubbles.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of rescue workers, making shifts, worked the whole
night on the rubbles but so far as the ICRC knows, only seven
people were found, six of them already dead, Golbe said.
</P>
<P>
The seventh, a Kenyan man, was found to be still alive but
serious injured when he was pulled out of the debris.
</P>
<P>
The rescue work was expected to last several days.
</P>
<P>
Eight Americans, including two women and one child, were
killed by the bombing and another 15 wounded with one still
missing, U.S. embassy spokesman Chris Scharf told Xinhua Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador Prundence Bushnell was seen to be taken out
into an ambulance vehicle minutes after the blast. She was
believed to be injured slightly but now the U.S. embassy said she
is OK and presiding over meetings.
</P>
<P>
U.S. medical and forensic experts arrived in the Kenyan
capital on Saturday as Washington launched an urgent
investigation into deadly car bomb attacks on two of its east
African embassies.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan police said they are probing the bomb blast which
is believed to be a terrorism attack aimed at the Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
