<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Close 7 Diplomatic Missions Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran has decided to close seven
diplomatic missions abroad, mainly in Africa, in line with the
government's austerity plan, local daily Tehran Times reported on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The seven missions to be closed down are Iranian embassies in
Sierra Leone, Burkina Faso, Tanzania, Gabon, Nicaragua,
Afghanistan and Iranian consulate in Hyderabad, India, the daily
said, adding the staff from the Iranian consulate in Turkey's
Trabuzan will be also reduced.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times, which was believed to be close to the Foreign
Ministry, quoted an informed source as saying that following an
austerity plan, the country would close the diplomatic missions
with immediate effect, which "economically and politically are not
viable."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi announced on
Wednesday that the ministry would close down a number of Iranian
missions abroad and reduce their staff in order to help the
government slash spendings.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to close our diplomatic missions in countries
which do not have very friendly relations with Iran and those
which do not have significant economic cooperation with our
country," Mohammadi said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came days after reports said that the country
would face a foreign exchange deficit of about 3.5 billion
U.S. dollars in the current Iranian year (starting from March 21)
since its foreign exchange revenue would be decreased to 9 billion
dollars from 14 billion dollars last Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami Sunday announced a package
of plans to rehabilitate the country's ailing oil-dependent
economy, saying that the government was facing mounting pressures
due to a sharp decrease in revenue as a result of oil price fall
during the past year.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the Iranian people would tolerate
more pressure in order to help the government solve economic
bottlenecks.
</P>
<P>
However, Tehran Times said that some officials were against
the decision to fully close those diplomatic missions and they
believed Iran's presence across the world was a must to air the
message and spirit of the Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
At this crucial juncture when Burkina Faso, the current
Chairman of the Organization of the African Unity, is playing a
central role for the African affairs, the closure of the Iranian
embassy in Ouagadougou is not good, the daily quoted an observer
as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
