<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Deputy PM Visits Iran to Enhance Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister
Jawad Anani left here Saturday for Tehran on an official visit
aimed at improving the bilateral ties after a 3-year period of
cold relations.
</P>
<P>
"After a break of several years, we believe that with the new
political leadership in Iran, the time is ripe to develop and
enhance bilateral ties on all levels,`` Anani, the prime minister
for development affairs, said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Anani, also the foreign minister, is expected
to deliver a good-will message from King Hussein of Jordan to
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami and invite him to pay an
official visit to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi and
other officials to discuss means of political and economic
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Among the issues to be raised with Iranian officials are
Iranian-Arab relations, elimination of mass-destruction weapons in
the Middle East, as well as the Arab-Israeli peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We will also discuss how to increase trade volume between the
two nations. We shall explore the industrial fields where we can
launch joint ventures," Anani said.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a joint venture to produce phosphate
fertilizer in Jordan to be mostly exported to Iran is on the
agenda of both sides' talks, according to Anani.
</P>
<P>
Tehran severed its diplomatic ties with Amman during the
8-year-old Iraqi-Iranian war on a perceived tilt of the kingdom
over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic ties between Jordan and Iran were resumed in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
However, in 1995 Jordan expelled the first secretary at the
Iranian Embassy Saeed Batini, charging him of "performing acts
that contradicted with his diplomatic status."
</P>
<P>
The ties between the two countries have cooled down since
then.
</P>
<P>
Both sides exchanged official visits in the past few years in
efforts to enhance bilateral ties, but the effect was limited.
</P>
<P>
After the moderate Khatami was elected Iranian president last
year, things began to turn for the better. Tehran`s ties were
enhanced not only with Jordan, but also with most of the Arab
states.
</P>
<P>
Last November, Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan visited Iran to
attend the Organization of Islamic Conference meetings, during
which he met Khatami and other senior officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
