<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Victims of Nairobi Bomb Attack Arrive in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Three American people, who
were injured in Friday's Nairobi bomb blast, arrived in Pretoria
Saturday morning after being evacuated by the South African Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
The three, one woman and two men, were loaded into waiting
ambulances on their arrival on Boeing 707 just after 8.40 a.m.,
senior military surgeon Dawie Roux said.
</P>
<P>
The woman was cut in the face, bruised and had a broken bone
in her left hand. She was taken from the aircraft on a stretcher.
The two men, one accompanied by his wife, walked to the
ambulances. Both had sustained head injures, Roux said.
</P>
<P>
Keith Betsch, American Military Attache, told local mass media
that the victims of the Nairobi bomb blast were widely dispersed
in at least four Nairobi hospitals. Many were in state of shock
and trauma and could therefore not be moved.
</P>
<P>
A massive blast on Friday morning damaged the U.S. embassy in
Nairobi, Kenya, killing about 80 people and injured over 2,000
others.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another bomb explosion took place near the American
embassy in Dar es Salaam, the capital of Tanzania. At least four
people were reportedly killed, and many others injured in the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
The South African foreign affairs department said it deplored
the bomb blasts, describing the attacks as "senseless". 
</P>
</TEXT>
