<HEADLINE> Iran Against Foreign Military Intervention in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has voiced Tehran's strong opposition to any foreign
military intervention in its northeastern neighbor Afghanistan,
the official news agency IRNA reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
No country should intervene and waste its potentials and
forces in the devastating civil war in Afghanistan, Kharrazi told
IRNA Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
Instead, all countries, including Afghanistan's neighbors, must
try to persuade the belligerent parties to engage in serious
negotiation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the remarks after the Afghan Taliban militia
launched large range of military offensives against its rival the
Northern Alliance headed by Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabani,
who was driven by Taliban from Kabul in September, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports said Taliban captured Mazar-I Sharif, the main
stronghold of the Northern Alliance on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Some reports from Afghanistan said that the Northern Alliance
accused Pakistan of sending troops to help Taliban in recent
fightings.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister warned that Iran cannot allow
security of this sensitive region to be played with and become a
tool for ambitions of others, urging the regional governments to
play a more constructive role in this respect.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi also noted that ethnic minorities in Afghanistan
instead of targeting one another should work to restore their
rights through political negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
