<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 08:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> King Hussein Allowed Leave From Clinic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein has been given a few
days' leave from the U.S. Mayo Clinic, where he had underwent the
first session of chemotherapy to treat the cancer of his lymphatic
tissue, the semi-official Jordan Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed to Crown Prince Hassan, the Regent, on
late Friday evening, King Hussein said he decided to go to
Washington and stay there on his leave, before returning again to
the clinic in Rochester, Minnesota, for more sessions of
treatment in the coming four to five months.
</P>
<P>
"Their (the doctors') decision came as a result of the
tangible progress in my condition, the improvement of the blood
count which as expected went down after the first cycle of
treatment as well as the accelerated progress towards normalcy,"
the king said in his letter.
</P>
<P>
Hussein also told Hassan that he is "pleasantly surprised" to
know that the doctors permitted him to leave the clinic for
Washington before starting a new round of chemotherapy on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate what he will do during his stay in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
The king added that his morale is high but he was advised by
the doctors "to avoid public places to protect against infection
before blood count goes back to normal and before starting the new
cycle of treatment."
</P>
<P>
Hussein, 62, has been hospitalized at the clinic since July 14
for suffering from non-Hodgkin's B-cell lymphoma, which is highly
treatable with chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to receive chemotherapy intravenously once
every 20 days over a period from four to five months.
</P>
<P>
The king underwent surgery to remove cancer from his ureter
and left kidney at the Mayo Clinic in 1992 and has had regular
medical checkups at the clinic since then.
</P>
<P>
In April 1997, he had surgery for an enlarged prostate that was
benign. He had an operation in November 1997 to remove an inflamed
lymph gland that was also found to be benign.
</P>
<P>
Hussein is the longest-reigning ruler in the Middle East. He is
due to celebrate 46 years on the throne on Tuesday. Hassan, his
brother, is the king's legal successor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
