<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Casualties Yet in Embankment Burst in Jiujiang: Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- No casualties have so far been
reported yet in the breach on the defence embankment in the city
of Jiujiang, in east China's Jiangxi Province, Governor Shu
Shengyou said here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The situation caused by the breach is expected to be brought
under control this evening," Shu told Xinhua, noting that life has
been by and large normal in urban Jiujiang.
</P>
<P>
So far, supplies of water, electricity and daily necessities
have been adequate as usual in the city.
</P>
<P>
The breach occurred Friday afternoon as floods kept surging in
the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of local residents, together with soldiers, have been
working to plug the breach for the past 27 hours, including
dumping eight boats loaded with rock, as well as thousands of
tons of rice, coal, soybeans, into the breached section.
</P>
<P>
Thirty trucks of rocks have arrived in Jiujiang from other
parts of the province under an emergency order of the provincial
government this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers are busy building a 90-meter long cofferdam
nearby the breached section.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang, with a population of about 500,000, is an industrial
center and tourist attraction located in the middle reaches of the
Yangtze River.  
</P>
</TEXT>
