<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 07:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Government Defends Privatization Plan of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian government will go
ahead with the sale of the Jordan Telecommunication Company (JTC)
despite of the criticism that the sale only benefits foreigners,
the semi-official Jordan Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Quoted in the newspaper, Deputy Prime Minister for Development
Affairs and Minister of Foreign Affairs Jawad Anani said 40
percent of JTC's shares will be sold to "a strategic partner."
</P>
<P>
"It is about state-of-the-art technology, then it can be
bought ...... We do not need anyone to teach us how to do our job
technically," said Anani who is also heading the Higher
Ministerial Committee for Privatization at the prime minister's
office.
</P>
<P>
Anani told the newspaper that two foreign companies have
already submitted their bids to become the strategic partner, who
will be obliged to inject new investment, update its technology,
establish incentive management mechanism and increase the
company's profits by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
The paper also quoted a government timetable as saying that
the British Cable and Wireless Company has submitted a bid worth
320 million U.S. dollars while the United States Southern Bell
Company offered half of that in its own bid.
</P>
<P>
The government has started to evaluate these bids, the
timetable said.
</P>
<P>
Anani made his remarks a week after the JTC's new Chairman of
Board Ali Shukri said that priority should be given to the
Jordanians, especially the JTC's employees, but not to a strategic
partner, in the selling of shares.
</P>
<P>
The partial sale of the JTC, whose asset stands at 1.2 billion
dollars, will make Jordan the first Arab country to allow private
or foreign ownership of its established telecommunication network.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government includes the privatization of the JTC
and other state-own companies as a major component of its reform
program to increase the role of the private sector, reduce its
direct participation in the productive sectors and help combat
poverty and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
However, the privatization plan can not become legal till now
because the parliament has been strongly opposing it. The
parliament said that the country needs extra laws to protect its
people who are easy to be hurt by the privatization plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Libyan FMs Hail Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan and his Libyan counterpart Omar Mustafa al-Muntasser
Saturday exchanged congratulation telegrams on the 20th
anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic ties between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tang said in a telegram that since China and Libya forged
diplomatic relations in 1978, their all-round friendly cooperative
ties have developed day by day.
</P>
