<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Leaders Arrive in Zimbabwe for DRC Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Seven heads of state and
government from southern and eastern Africa are scheduled to hold
an emergency meeting Saturday to discuss the widening rift and
tension between the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and its
neighbors, Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The leaders arrived in the city of Victoria Falls of Zimbabwe
Friday night to attend the meeting called by Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni at the second Southern African International
Dialog in Namibia's coastal city of Swakopmund at the end of
July.
</P>
<P>
The summit was initially scheduled to discuss the
reconciliation of differences between DRC and its neighbors,
Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
But because of the growing discontent with DRC President
Laurent Kabila's leadership, spearheaded by the Tutsi-dominated
opposition, the meeting will also focus on how to persuade
President Kabila to negotiate with the rebels, sources said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Museveni and Kabila, and lately the growing
tension between Kabila and Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu
and other Rwandan leaders, have become a source of worry to
leaders in both east and southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Stability in the Great Lakes region can never be a reality so
long as these tensions exist.
</P>
<P>
The seven leaders to attend the summit are Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe, Ugandan President Museveni, Tanzanian
President Benjamin Mkapa, Zambian President Frederick Chiluba,
Namibian President Sam Nujoma, Rwandan President Bizimungu and
DRC President Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
