<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Embankment Breach Widens Because of Mechanical Mishaps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The breach on the defence
embankment in the city of Jiujiang, in east China's Jiangxi
Province, somewhat expanded owing to mechanical mishaps resultant
from bigger water flows.
</P>
<P>
A barge called in urgently to pitch in the effort to plug up
the breach went out of control because of a sudden power cut. It
then was swept down to a sunk boat loaded with stone on the right
side of the breach, making the stones at and around the boat's
bottom unfastened and washed away by swift rapids, which then
widened the breach from 40 meters to 60 meters and resulted in
significantly larger water flows.
</P>
<P>
The breach occured at around 4:00 Friday afternoon as floods
kept surging.
</P>
<P>
As cranes cannot go into operation, the iron containers filled
with rocks cannot be thrown in to stop the breach.
</P>
<P>
Right now, efforts are being intensified to tow away the barge
and cast in more rocks and stones. Policemen are also working hard
to drive in piles to reinforce the anti-flood embankment.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the delayed supply of rocks and stones is
hindering the refitting of the dyke. And an urgent order has been
issued to transport in 20 freight trucks of rocks and stone from
Nanchang, the Provincial capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
