<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 07:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Opposition Demands Peace Treaty With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- A coalition of Jordan's opposition
parties has blamed last month's water pollution in west Amman on
Israel and called for the government to terminate the peace treaty
it signed with Israel in 1994, according to a statement obtained
by Xinhua here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The temporarily-organized coalition, which includes the most
influential opposition party, the Islamic Action Front, said in
the statement that the polluted water, that has left many people
hospitalized for diarrhea and nausea-related diseases and caused
panic all over the capital since July 5, came from Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The polluted water coming from the Lake Tiberias (in Israel)
is a result of the peace treaty. Therefore, the coalition urges
all local powers to unify their efforts to abrogate the treaty,"
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Jordan reached a peace agreement in 1994, under
which Jordan was allowed to store 50 million cubic meters of water
in the Lake Tiberias each winter and then reclaim it in summer.
</P>
<P>
In early July, the residents in west Amman began to complain
of discolored and foul-smelling tap water. Recent investigations
of the Jordanian Royal Scientific Society said that there was a
high concentration of algae in the water coming from the Lake
Tiberias and the Yarmouk River, which are the major water
sources for Amman.
</P>
<P>
The water treatment plant for the capital failed to treat the
water in time, thus causing the pollution.
</P>
<P>
The government has not drawn its own conclusion of the issue
yet. A special commission is still working to specify the
pollution source and find the persons responsible for the issue.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-Israel peace treaty used to be criticized by the
House of Representatives, where the opposition parties share a
number of seats, while the government is determined to carry it
out and insists on normalization of ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the two Arab countries to sign peace treaty
with Israel and sticks to normalization of ties with the Jewish
state. The other is Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
