<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 06:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Government in Crisis Over Water Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Recent water scandal has pushed
the Jordanian government into a deep crisis, as King Hussein
lashed it for negligence and the parliament as well as the
opposition parties demanded its resignation.
</P>
<P>
The king now hospitalized in the United States, in a letter to
Crown Prince Hassan, the Regent on late Friday evening criticized
the government as "being lax in carrying out its duties and
responsibilities," especially on the recent water pollution issue.
</P>
<P>
Panic hit Amman on July 5, as many citizens, especially those
in the western part of the city, found discolored water coming out
of taps with a strange smell and taste. The situation was brought
to control a week later.
</P>
<P>
The king blamed the government for not being able to produce a
reasonable explanation and specify the pollution source yet.
</P>
<P>
This makes it imperative to "take proper action against any
mistake or act of negligence," said the king, who is the supreme
leader of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
He added that he hoped a special commission established earlier
this week will find the pollution source and spotting the persons
responsible for this incident that have left many people
hospitalized for diarrhea and nausea-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Agricultural and Water Committee under
the Lower House of Parliament, submitted a report to the house
speaker, demanding the resignation and trial of Minister of Water
and Mineral Resources Munther Haddadin and the Jordan Water
Authority's Secretary-General Munther Khleifat for their role in
"causing the problem."
</P>
<P>
The committee in its investigation report released on Tuesday
said the source of polluted water was from the Tiberias Lake and
the Yarmouk River bordering Israel, adding diplomatic color to the
issue.
</P>
<P>
A coalition of Jordanian opposition parties, in a statement
obtained by Xinhua here Saturday, even urged the whole government
to resign over the scandal. The issue was called as "the month-old
water crisis that has caused nationwide panic" in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Jordan Times Saturday quoted Prime Minister
Abdul-Salam Majali as saying in Amman that any person found to be
responsible for the incident will be punished.
</P>
<P>
Majali arrived in Amman later Friday after meeting the king in
the U.S.. He said that he did not discuss with the king the
demanded resignation of his government.
</P>
<P>
Majali said "The things have not developed to that extent (of
resignation) and unfortunately, every now and then, we find some
people who wish or desire the resignation of the government."
</P>
<P>
The current government was appointed by the king in March,
1997 and later underwent a small reshuffle. But many said the
government's overall performance are unsatisfactory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another 6 Found Dead in Nairobi Bomb Blast Scene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Another six bodies of people
were found overnight from the rubbles of the bomb blast rocking
downtown Nairobi Friday, putting the confirmed death toll to
nearly 90, the International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) said.
</P>
<P>
The death toll for sure will exceed 100, ICRC information
officer Nina Golbe told Xinhua by phone Saturday morning. The
bomb blew up near the U.S. Embassy in a very busy commercial
area.
</P>
<P>
She said until 11:00 p.m. Friday, more than 1,100 people had
been dropped to hospitals, only 75 of them were discharged
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of rescues workers, making shifts, worked through the
whole night on the rubbles but so far as the ICRC knows, only
seven people were found, six of them already dead, Golbe said.
</P>
<P>
The seventh, a Kenyan man, was found to be still alive but
serious injured when he was pulled out of the debris.
</P>
<P>
Eight Americans, including two women and one child, were
killed by the bombing and another 15 wounded with one still
missing, U.S. embassy spokesman Chris Scharf told Xinhua Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador Prudence Bushnell was seen to be taken out
into an ambulance minutes after the blast. She was believed to
be slightly injured but now the U.S. Embassy said she is OK and
is presiding over a meeting.
</P>
<P>
U.S. medical and forensic experts were due in the Kenyan
capital on Saturday as Washington launched an urgent
investigation into deadly car bomb attacks on two of its east
African embassies. Another one occurred in Tanzanian capital Dar
es Salaam at about 10:45 a.m. Friday, some ten minutes after the
Nairobi blast.
</P>
<P>
Ufundi Co-op House -- a five-story office block between the
U.S. embassy and the 22-story Co-operative Bank House -- was
turned into a pile of debris.
</P>
<P>
The whole rear wall of the U.S. embassy was gone, leaving five
rows of smoke-blackened empty rooms staring at the leaden sky.
</P>
<P>
At least two big buses full of passengers were seriously
damaged as they passed the building when the bomb blew up, more
than 20 passengers have been confirmed dead.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of vehicles were also damaged on the scene, which is a
very busy commercial area of the Kenyan capital.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Trade Minister Joseph Kamotho have sustained slight
injuries. The minister and the U.S. ambassador met in Kamotho's
office in the raided building half an hour before the blast.
</P>
<P>
The rescue work was expected to last several days.
</P>
<P>
"The rescue is ongoing. We are doing everything possible to
help those wounded and... to make sure everyone moved out of the
ruins," said the U.S. embassy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi late Friday inspected the
blast scene and visited victims at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
He said he was deeply shocked and condemned the attack, vowing
to try best "to bring the perpetrators of the heinous crime to
book."
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan police said Friday evening that it highly suspects
that the bomb blast is a terrorism attack aimed at the Americans.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the bomb explosion near the U.S. embassy
in Dar es Salaam killed at least six people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
