<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Jury Awards $760 Million to Ex-Lockheed Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A California jury has awarded
760.6 million U.S. dollar in punitive damages to 38 former Lockheed
Corp. employees who claimed they were harmed by toxic chemicals while
building the stealth fighter for the company, a lawyer for the
defendants said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Superior Court lawsuit was filed by former employees who worked
on the radar-evading jet during the 1960s, 1970s and 1980s, plaintiff
lawyer Thomas Girardi said in a statement, claiming the workers were
never advised of the danger posed by the chemicals.
</P>
<P>
In the lawsuits, the workers said that they suffered health
problems ranging from headaches and skin rashes to terminal cancers as
a result of exposure to various chemicals used in building the stealth
fighter.
</P>
<P>
The verdict against five chemical manufacturers including Exxon
Corp., Unocal Corp., Ashland Inc., Shell Oil Co. and DuPont, but not
against Lockheed, was reached Thursday and announced Friday. It
follows a compensatory damages verdict last week in which the workers
were awarded 25.4 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The latest lawsuit is among several filed by Ex-Lockheed workers
and residents who lived near Lockheed's secret plant which, according
to Associated Press, produced top secret airplanes, including the
stealth fighter and U-2 spy plane.
</P>
<P>
Spokesmen for both Unocal Corp. and Exxon Corp. said their
companies would appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
