<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lin Ti-Chuan's Body Returns to Taiwan Via HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The body of Lin Ti-chuan, a
Taiwanese woman who had died during a business trip on the
mainland, left Beijing for Taiwan via Hong Kong this morning.
</P>
<P>
Ten of Lin's family members and relatives aboard the CA101
flight carrying Lin's casket left here at 7:50 this morning for
Taiwan via Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Liu Gangqi, deputy secretary-general of the Association for
Relations Across the Taiwan Strait (Arats), who had just returned
from Haicheng city in Liaoning Province Friday afternoon, saw
Lin's family members and relatives off at capital airport and
expressed sympathy and condolences to them.
</P>
<P>
An official with Air China made a special trip to the airport
to receive Lin's family members and relatives at six am today. The
airlines opened a special counter to handle boarding procedures
for Lin's family, and sent two crew members to help them consign
luggages. And the customs and border check also provide them with
special easy accesses.
</P>
<P>
Na Bao'en, general manager of Air China who is on duty, said
his airlines had been asked by the Civil Aviation Administration
of China (CAAC) on Thursday to do transportation smoothly, and Air
China immediately made arrangements on the return of Lin's family
members and relatives as well as the transportation of Lin's
casket. The first two front rows of seats in the cabin were
reserved for Lin's family and relatives, who were treated as the
top group of guests on board.
</P>
<P>
After Lin's casket arrived at the airport yesterday afternoon,
the crew took prompt measures to look after it well, according to
Wang Fengping, chief of the cargo transportation sector of Air
China. The casket was placed at the front part of the cargo bay,
so as to make sure that it can be moved smoothly and properly
after arrival in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Representative of Lin's close relatives voiced gratitude to Air
China for its sound arrangements. Yuan Saibing from a travel
agency to host Lin's family members and relatives, said the Lins
repeatedly thanked for the goods arrangements during their stay
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
After the CA101 flight took off, the airlines soon faxed the
location of Lin's casket in the cargo bay and seat numbers of
Lin's family members and relatives to Hong Kong airport, so that
they will be well received there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
