<HEADLINE> Hi-Tech Companies Offered Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Science and
Technology will work together with other relevant departments to
spell out potential pitfalls of entering stock markets to help
hi-tech medium and small-sized firms raise capital, today's "China
Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The move will help hi-tech companies that would otherwise be
unable to raise the money needed to expand without offering stock,
Minister Xu Guanhua said at the start of a national conference
held yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which ends tomorrow, was held to mark the 10th
anniversary of the Torch Programme -- a national plan implemented
with the State Council's approval to propel regional economic
growth through developing hi-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has decided to allocate special funds to fuel
the development of medium- and small-sized firms, which contribute
two-third of the total output generated by the country's
industrial companies. Xu said.
</P>
<P>
But a lack of start-up capitals is hindering China's hi-tech
development, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the State will start hi-tech business incubators
in universities to exploit their brain power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
