<HEADLINE> Houston Beats Detroit, Sacramento Downs Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Houston Comets rallied for
their ninth straight road win by beating the Detroit Shock 61-57
on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Cynthia Cooper returned from a bruised quad in the first half
to tie her own league season-high of 34 points. Cooper, the WNBA
Most Valuable Player, missed more than six minutes of the first
half with the injury and the Shock took advantage with a 12-2
burst that opened a nine-point lead. She returned to score
Houston's final six points of the half, but Detroit still held a
33-20 lead at interval.
</P>
<P>
There was no stopping Cooper in the second half. She scored 13
points in the first nine minutes as Houston pulled into a tie,
then gave the Comets the lead for good at 54-51 with one of her
four three-points with 6:39 remaining.
</P>
<P>
Cooper also holds the all-time WNBA single-game record with 44
points in 1997. This season, she leads the league in scoring at
better than 23 points per game.
</P>
<P>
Kim Perrot added 15 points for the Comets who ranked first on
the WNBA standings with 25 wins against two losses. Cindy Brown
had 13 points and 13 rebounds to lead a balanced attack for the
Shock,who had a six-game home winning streak snapped and fell four
games behind the first-place Charlotte Sting in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
Hlede and Razija Mujanovic scored 12 points apiece and Sandy
Brondello added 10 for Detroit, which shot 42 percent from the
field and held a 39-25 rebounding edge. Houston shot 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the another game, Sacramento Monarchs beat Washington Mysti
cs 76-55. 
</P>
</TEXT>
