<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Indonesia plans to buy 500,000 tons of rice from
Thailand for about 6 billion baht (150 million U.S. dollars), The
Bangkok Post said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Supachai Panitchpakdi, Thailand's deputy prime minister and
commerce minister, signed a memorandum with Ahmed Musih Saefuddin,
 Indonesia's state minister for food and horticulture, here on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the memorandum, 400,000 tons of rice will be bought on
three years' credit while cash will be paid for the rest.
</P>
<P>
The rice is for delivery between September and January at
280-282 dollars per ton, the newspaper quoted sources familiar
with the deal as saying. (Thailand-Indonesia-Rice)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil, the biggest producer and exporter of
coffee in the world, has seen coffee sales abroad reduced by 27
percent during the first six months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Data released by the Brazilian Association of Coffee Exporters
showed that from January to June, coffee exports amounted to 5.6
million 60-kilogram bags, with a total income of 1.02 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The main buyers of Brazilian coffee are the United States and
Germany. The U.S. imported 728,300 bags and Germany bought 669,900
bags. (Brazil-Coffee Exports)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Four banks under the supervision of the Indonesian
Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) have been declared insolvent, the
press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Audits have been finalized in respect of the six major private
 banks taken over by IBRA in April. Shareholders' rights have been
 transferred to IBRA and insolvency declarations have been made in
 four of the cases," the government was quoted as saying in a
letter to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on Friday as part
of a series of regular updates on the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has pledged a 43 billion U.S. dollar bailout package to
help Indonesia deal with its economic crisis. As part of the
government's sweeping economic reforms that focused on banking
restructuring, six ailing banks were taken over by IBRA in April.
(Indonesia-Banks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The U.S. dollar rose nearly 2 yen Friday after
traders dumped the Japanese currency at the disappointing speech
of Japan's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Investors were waiting for new programs from the new government
to revive the economy, but they heard no new measures from Keizo
Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 146.13
Japanese yen, up from 144.32 late Thursday. The U.S. currency also
was changing hands at 1.7792 German marks, up from 1.7725. (New
York-Dollar Stronger)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam on Friday effectively devalued its currency,
the dong, by about seven percent, bowing to pressure resulting
from the financial crisis that has ravaged Southeast Asia since
July last year.
</P>
<P>
On Friday morning, the State Bank of Vietnam lowered the
official rate of the dong to the dollar by 10 percent from 11,816
on Thursday to 12,998, while simultaneously narrowing the trading
band on either side of this rate from 10 to seven
percent. (Vietnam-Devaluation) 
</P>
</TEXT>
