<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enhanced Efforts Continued to Plug Up Breach in Jiujiang Dykes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The 40-meter breach on the
defence embankment in the city of Jiujiang, in east Jiangxi
Province, is expected to be plugged up in around 24 hours if all
essential materials are supplied without fail.
</P>
<P>
Eight boats have been sunk into the breach to stop leaking
water and floods at both the upper and lower reaches have been
largely brought under control, but water is continuing to bubble
out from the hull of the boats, according to Yang Guangxu, head of
a specialists' team of the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
At about 1:10 pm Friday, a water-sodden point was found at the
defence dyke about five km from the city proper. The point was
enlarged into a two-feet leakage in less than 20 minutes, and at
2:00 pm, the embankments partially collapsed. At around 4:00 pm, a
breach of 45 meters was shaped and two-meter deep water began to
inundate the western parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
Right now, a 90-m-long protective shelter is being erected
right outside the breached dyke and a 80-m-long cofferdam built
inside the dyke, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
At least 25,000 cubic meters of crushed rocks and stone and
other filling materials are required to fill in a six-m section
between the protective shelter and the cofferdam to reinforce the
dyke and stop water flow.
</P>
<P>
Experts are considering throwing filled bags into pre-made
steel frames or setting up scaffolds of steel pipes to block
intruding water.
</P>
<P>
The main difficulty right now lies in the lack of stones and
other filling materials, as there are less than 10,000 tons of
crushed stone available. At least three boats carrying coals and
sand have arrived at the spot, with more expected to rush in.
</P>
<P>
So far stone, soybean, rice, and coal have been used, among
other things, to fill in bags used to block leaking water.
</P>
<P>
The local Flood Control Headquarters has urged residents to
evacuate the area. More than 30,000 civilians and soliders, many
of whom have not eaten for a whole day, are working hard shoulder
by shoulder to refit the dyke.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang City, along the southern bank of the middle reaches of
the Yangtze River, lies in the northern part of Jiangxi
Province. The city proper covers a 42 sq km area with a population
of some 500,000.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang is dotted with lakes and rivers, of which the most
well-known is the Poyang Lake, the country's largest freshwater
lake. For weeks, the 3,976-sq-km lake has maintained record
flooding water levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
