<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banks to Refinance Clients of Property Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Customers of 164 housing and
condominium development projects in Thailand, which have been
unable to transfer completed units after their financiers were
shut down, can start applying for refinancing from two state banks
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Nation newspaper said Saturday that Government Housing Bank
and Government Savings Bank have agreed to spend 19.7 billion baht
(492.5 million U.S. dollars) to bail out those customers.
</P>
<P>
House buyers are required to contact the National Housing
Authority, the middleman of the program, which will forward their
applications to the two banks.
</P>
<P>
The program has been initiated by the government to help
property buyers who have been affected by last year's closure of
56 finance companies.
</P>
<P>
Normally, property developers pledge land plots with financial
institutions for an amount of money to cover construction costs.
After the 56 companies were shut down, the projects-in-progress
ran into a liquidity crunch and land ownership could not be
transferred to buyers.
</P>
<P>
The two banks agreed to lend up to 70 percent of the appraised
value of properties which are more than 90 percent complete. For
projects that are more than 50 percent complete, the banks will
lend 70 percent of the appraised land value and 80 percent of
construction costs.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Thailand's property sector could see recovery
within the next three to five years, after land ownership limits
and restrictions are eased for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The government is in the process of amending a law to allow
foreigners to lease properties for up to 100 years, instead of the
current limit of 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Elevated Rail To Be Built In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has already received
approval from the State Council to build China's first elevated
rail, which is expected to open in July 2000, according to today's
"China Daily."
</P>
<P>
The billion-dollar, 25-kilometer-long rail starts at Caohejing
in Xuhui District and ends at Jiangwan Town in Hongkou District
with 19 stops on the way.
</P>
<P>
A short 3.5-km stretch of the proposed rail will be built at
ground level, said Tan Qikun, deputy director of the Shanghai
Construction Commission.
</P>
<P>
The rail will have connections with subways, trains, and buses
at Caohejing, Shanghai Stadium, Hongqiao Station, the Shanghai
Railway Sation, and at Baoshan, Tan said.
</P>
<P>
The first phase is expected to cost about 8.6 billion yuan
(1.03 billion US dollars) with each kilometer of rail costing 344
million yuan (41 million US dollars), Tan said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has set up a company with a registered capital of 2.7
billion yuan (325 million US dollars) to oversee the project. The
company has invested about three billion yuan (362 million US
dollars) in the project and plans to borrow 190 million US dollars
in loans from foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
The stretch of tracks has already been dismantled, 430,000
square meters of housing have been demolished and the 5,400
families and 500 businesses located near the tracks have been
relocated. The city will finish laying tracks and decorating
stations by next June.
</P>
<P>
Trains, driving at a speed of 35 kilometers per hour and
arriving every 5.5 minutes, will carry 730,000 passengers daily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
