<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Coffee Exports Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Brazil, the biggest
producer and exporter of coffee in the world, has seen coffee
sales abroad reduced by 27 percent during the first six months of
1998.
</P>
<P>
Data released by the Brazilian Association of Coffee Exporters
showed that from January to June, coffee exports amounted to 5.6
million 60-kilogram bags, with a total income of 1.020 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The main buyers of Brazilian coffee are the United States and
Germany. The U.S. imported 728,300 bags and Germany bought 669,900
bags.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Esteve, president of the association, said the reduction
in exports was caused by the drop in supply. The previous harvest
produced only 22.5 million bags, the least of this decade. But the
situation of the next six months will improve and coffee sales
will increase from 10 to 11 million bags.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said the coffee output will surpass 30
million bags this year, with a growth of more than 30 percent over
last year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil exports about 15 million bags of coffee every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Foreign Reserves Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's foreign reserves fell
by 700 million U.S. dollars to 26.8 billion dollars as of July 31
from the previous week due to the central bank's settlement of
forward contract obligations.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand said in a statement available Saturday
that net forward obligations declined by 900 million dollars to
stay at 11.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
Reserve money, comprising notes and coins in circulation plus
deposits of financial institutions at the central bank, increased
by 3.7 billion baht (92.5 million dollars) over the period to
448.1 billion baht (11.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The statement said reserve money rose on cash demand by the
public, but deposits of financial institutions at the central bank
declined as they needed to make their provisional reserves for the
period between July 23 and August 7.
</P>
<P>
As of July 31, the central bank's net obligations to the
government amounted to 13.1 billion baht (327.5 million dollars),
down from 25 billion baht (625 million dollars) the week before.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the central bank's net claims on financial
institutions rose 16.5 billion baht (412.5 million dollars) to
133.4 billion baht (3.34 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The statement said the domestic liquidity was tight in the
beginning of the week to July 31 but eased later.
</P>
<P>
The overnight repurchase rate dropped from a range of 10
percent to 11.13 percent per year on July 24 to a range of 8.75
percent to 11.375 percent on July 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
