<HEADLINE> US Wants to Patrol Costa Rican Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States Ambassador to
Costa Rica Thomas Dodd reiterated the interest of his country in
patrolling Costa Rican waters to combat drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
During a Thursday meeting with the head of the governing Social
Christian Unity (PUSC) parliamentary caucus Ovidio Pacheco, Dodd
repeated his government's proposal which was rejected last year by
the previous government on grounds that it violated the
constitutional norms of the country.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica bars the entrance to its waters by armed ships of
other countries without authorization of the congress.
</P>
<P>
Drug traffickers ofter use Central America as a transit between
Colombia and the consumer countries, especially the United States
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Washington wants to strike agreements with Central American
countries on joint patrols to crack down on the crime. A similar
proposal was also rejected by Nicaragua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
