<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts Continued to Plug Up Breach in Jiujiang Dykes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Eight boats have been sunk into
a 40-meter breach of the defence embankment in the city of
Jiujiang, in east China's Jiangxi Province, but the flooding
situation has not yet been brought under control.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of people are throwing bags filled with coal
into pre-made steel frames to plug up water sneaking out into the
city through gaps between the sunken boats.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation has not improved substantially as some
old gaps continue to gush out water and new gaps appeared between
the boats, and there are cracks in hulls of some boats, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
At about 12:30 Friday, a water-sodden point was found at the
city defence dyke. The point was enlarged into a two feet leakage
in less than an hour and, at 4:00 pm, the embankments partially
collapsed. Then, the two-meter deep water began to inundate the
western parts of the city through a 40-meter breach.
</P>
<P>
Stone, soybean, rice, and coal have been used, among other
things, to fill in bags used to block leaking water.
</P>
<P>
The local Flood Control Headquarters has urged residents to
evacuate the area.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang City, along the southern bank of the middle reaches of
the Yangtze River, lies in the northern part of Jiangxi
Province. The city proper covers a 42 sq km area with a population
of some 500,000.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang is dotted with lakes and rivers, of which the most
well-known is the Poyang Lake, the country's largest freshwater
lake. For weeks, the 3,976-sq-km lake has maintained record
flooding water levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
