<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran President-Elect Names New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Ecuadoran President-elect Jamil
Mahuad Witt has named his future cabinet, which includes three
woman ministers, the Information Ministry announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The three woman ministers are Interior Minister Ana Lucia
Armijos, Tourism Minister Rocio Vasquez and Minister of
Environment Yolanda Kakabadse.
</P>
<P>
Current Foreign Minister Jose Ayala Lasso will continue to
occupy his post in the new cabinet, while retired army officer
Jose Gallardo Roman will be defense minister.
</P>
<P>
The president-elect's close friend Jaime Duran will be the new
government's secretary-general, who is in charge of all government
affairs and coordinates works among government, parliament,
parties and ministries, the equivalent of a prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Other new faces are:
</P>
<P>
-- Finance Minister Fidel Jaramillo;
</P>
<P>
-- Hector Plaza Saavedra, the minister of industry, trade and
fisheries;
</P>
<P>
-- Patricio Ribadeneira, minister of energy and mines;
</P>
<P>
-- Emilio Gallardo Gonzanlez, minister of agriculture and
livestock;
</P>
<P>
-- Teodoro Pena, minister of housing and urban development;
</P>
<P>
-- Guillermo Celi, minister of social welfare;
</P>
<P>
-- Raul Samaniego, minister of public works and communications;
</P>
<P>
-- Labour Minister Angel Polibio Chaves;
</P>
<P>
-- Health Minister Edgar Rodas Andrade;
</P>
<P>
-- Vladimiro Alvarez, minister of education and culture.
</P>
<P>
The information ministry is removed from the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Jamil Mahuad will be sworn in next Monday. He will be the
country's president until January 15, 2003. 
</P>
