<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More than 570 Ancient Tombs Excavated in Hebei Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- More than 570 ancient tombs
that dated back to 506 B.C. have been discovered in Lingshou
County in north China's Hebei Province with more than 1,700 relics
unearthed.
</P>
<P>
Discovered by railway construction workers, the tombs fall into
three layers. Tombs at the bottom are of the Zhongshan State (506
B.C.-296 B.C.) of the Zhou Dynasty; the tombs on the middle level
were built in the Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-220 A.D.) and tombs in the
upper layer are of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) and the Qing
Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
Unearthed relics include bronzeware, jadeware and pottery, most
of which were from Zhongshan period.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, archeologists estimate that there are another 300
ancient tombs under the site.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Armor Restored in Jiangsu Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have taken
over two months to retore ancient armor dating to the Western Han
Dynasty (206 B.C.-24 A.D.) in Xuzhou, a city in the northern part
of east China's Jiangsu Province, according to the Shanghai-based
"Wenhui Daily."
</P>
<P>
Archeologists with the Xuzhou Terra Cotta Warrior Museum have
assembled thousands of iron pieces of armor unearthed from a
mausoleum.
</P>
<P>
An analysis has been performed on the iron pieces which led
researchers to conclude that they belong to six types of armors,
which include some never found before.
</P>
<P>
The restoration work is significant for research on ancient
China's military weaponry, metallurgy and clothing, archeologists
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
