<HEADLINE> Spain, Norway Condemn Bomb Explosions in Kenya, Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Spanish government condemned
the two bomb explosions that occurred near U.S. embassies and
killed more than 81 people in Kenya and Tanzania on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish Foreign Ministry said in a statement that the
Spanish government denounced the brutal criminal actions and
expressed great indignation over the act of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish government also expressed deep condolences to the
families of the dead.
</P>
<P>
In Oslo, Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek also
condemned the terrorist bombings in the two African countries.
</P>
<P>
She said it was a great tragedy that innocent people were
victims of the violence. She said the international community must
seek ways to fight against terrorism to prevent such crimes.
</P>
<P>
Two bombs exploded outside the U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania Friday. At least 81 people were killed and more than
1,700 others have suffered injuries.
</P>
<P>
At least 74, including eight Americans, were killed in Nairobi,
the capital of Kenya, and more than 1,640 wounded. At least seven
were reported dead in Tanzanian capital of Dar es Salaam and 72
others were hurt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
