<HEADLINE> Philippines' Budget Deficit Shrinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's budget
deficit declined considerably in the first seven months of this
year due to improving revenue performance in July, a newspaper
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit narrowed to 13.6 billion pesos (25 million
U.S. dollars) from January to the end of July from 24 billion
pesos (60 million dollars) during the first semester in 1998, said
the newspaper Today, citing figures from the finance department.
</P>
<P>
For the month of July, the government generated a surprise cash
budget surplus of 10.4 billion pesos (26 million dollars) with
revenues of 52.9 billion pesos (1.3 billion dollars) and
expenditures of 42.5 billion pesos (1.06 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government, which has estimated a staggering budget deficit
of 70 billion pesos (1.75 billion dollars) this year, is trying to
limit this year's budget deficit to 40 billion pesos (1 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Savings-generating measures and additional revenues from
additional tax measures are being considered to bring down the
rising deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
