<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Water Levels Rising Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Flood situation in central China's
Hubei Province remained severe this morning as water levels of the
Yangtze River surged to new heights, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
At 8:00 am today, water level at the Shashi Measuring
Point, upstream of Wuhan, the provincial capital, climbed to 44.94
m, compared with 44.92 m at mid-night Friday.
</P>
<P>
The water level has further approached the level for a proposed
diversion program to discharge flood waters into the Jingjiang
diversion zone, in Gong'an County, some 200 kilometers of Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
So far some 250,000 local residents in the zone have been
evacuated to make way for the planned diversion. The Chinese
authorities plan to relocate a total of 330,000 local residents
from the diversion zone, to protect the major cities downstream.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, data obtained from 2:00 am through 7:00 am this
morning indicate that the water flow rate at Shashi stood around
48,200 cubic meters per second.  
</P>
</TEXT>
