<HEADLINE> Four Indonesian Banks Declared Insolvent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Four banks under the supervision
of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) have been
declared insolvent, the local press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Audits have been finalized in respect of the six major private
banks taken over by IBRA in April. Shareholders' rights have been
transferred to IBRA and insolvency declarations have been made in
four of the cases," the government was quoted as saying in a
letter to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on Friday as part
of a series of regular updates on the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has pledged a 43 billion U.S. dollar bailout package to
help Indonesia deal with its economic crisis. As part of the
government's sweeping economic reforms that focused on banking
restructuring, six ailing banks were taken over by IBRA in April.
</P>
<P>
They include Bank Danamon, Bank BDNI, Bank Umum Nasional, Bank
Tiara Asia, Bank Modern and Bank PDFCI.
</P>
<P>
However, the government declined to reveal the names of the
four banks declared insolvent.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, demands have mounted that the
government take legal action against those responsible for the
insolvencies, including both bankers and owners.
</P>
<P>
The letter to the IMF also said the government expected the
economy to contract by 15 percent this year, but was optimistic
that the country will record a positive growth in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The government was working toward achieving single-digit
inflation within no more than two years, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
Year-end inflation is forecast to reach 80 percent this year.
An inflation of almost 60 percent was recorded between January and
July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
