<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Wood Industries Face Shortage of Logs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian wood-processing
industries are facing a severe shortage of logs, the local press
Saturday quoted the Indonesian Forestry Society (MPI) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The country's processing capacities have exceeded log output,
said MPI chairman Sudrajat.
</P>
<P>
The supply shortage is partly due to a lack of coordination
among related government agencies such as the Ministry of Forestry
and Plantations, the Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) and the
Ministry of Industry and Trade.
</P>
<P>
"BKPM issued permits to develop wood-processing industries
without calculating the log supply with the Ministry of Forestry
and Plantations," Sudrajat said.
</P>
<P>
Local wood-processing businesses would need about 35 million to
36 million cubic meters a year while the supply of logs would only
total 26 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
"Wood-processing industries are only operating at 30 percent to
40 percent of their production capacity due to the scarcity of
logs," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
