<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PFA Chief: Stars Deserve Their Payment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Professional
Footballers'Association has defended its members after a report
revealed the spiralling wages enjoyed by Premier League stars.
</P>
<P>
Top flight salaries were criticised in the 1998 Deloitte &AMP;
Touche Annual Review of Football Finance when the report said
money was bypassing the lower leagues and going straight into
players' pockets.
</P>
<P>
But PFA deputy chief executive Brendon Batson claimed: "It is
only right that the reason for the success should benefit from it."
</P>
<P>
The former Arsenal and West Brom star believes that clubs have
to constantly improve salaries to achieve that success.
</P>
<P>
"It has always been the case in a labour intensive industry
that the biggest thing for clubs would be the players' wages and
nothing has changed in that respect," Batson said.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in wages has been a trend over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
"It has always been a concern with the formation of the Premier
League that clubs in the lower divisions would suffer because the
monies are being pooled at the top end.
</P>
<P>
"It is like any employer who is looking at his wage bill. It's
about investment. The reason why clubs are investing heavily in
their players is because they are looking at what they can
generate at the end.
</P>
<P>
"It is not surprising to see that the four top clubs in the
Premier League have the highest wage bill because they can see
that is linked to success.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question that most clubs now in the Premier League
regard success as retaining their status as much as chasing
silverware," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
