<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Gain Modestly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks extended a
modest rebound from Tuesday's selloff, but failed in a sharper
rally today as Japan's new leader did not offer measures to revive
the nation's sticky economy.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average finished just 20.34 points
higher at 8,598.02 after retreating from a midday gain of 132
points, closing the week about 740 points below the record of
9,337.97 set three weeks ago on July 17. It was also down 285.27
points for the whole week.
</P>
<P>
Technology shares led the Nasdaq market to a second day of big
gains, but the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 finished a shade lower.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 0.18 to 1,089.45, and the Nasdaq
composite index rose 17.26 to 1,846.77.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 756.26 million shares,
down a bit from 759.75 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 1.70 to 549.50, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 7.12 to 684.07.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 9.18 to
415.80.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department report also showed that wages -- which
often account for two-thirds of a product's price -- rose at a
slower pace in July.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate held steady at 4.5 percent, matching
June's rate and only slightly higher than the 28-year low of 4.3
percent reached in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
