<HEADLINE> Angolan Govt Resumes Talks with UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government Friday
resumed talks with the rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) after two months of suspension.
</P>
<P>
The talks, attended by U.N. special envoy Lakhdar Brahimi,
discussed some unsettled issues for the 1994 Lusaka peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process was thrown into crisis after the
sudden death of former U.N. Angolan representative Alioune Beye
on June 26.
</P>
<P>
UNITA delegation chairman Isalas Samakuva suggested to
postpone the date for the re-establishment of governmental
administrations in the four towns in central Angola.
</P>
<P>
The towns are Bailundo, Andulo, Mungo and Nharea.
</P>
<P>
Samakuva said that the suggestion might be the only result, if
any, of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Higino Carneiro, the deputy chairman of the government
delegation said after the talks that he could not guarantee that
the country is at present away from war.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the hope of the peace process in Angola would
have to be put on the shoulders of the newly-named U.N.
representative to Angola, Issa Diallo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
