<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Continues to Rise Against Yen, Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose nearly 2
yen Friday after traders dumped the Japanese currency at the
disappointing speech of Japan's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Investors were waiting for new programs from the new government
to revive the economy, but they heard no new measures from Keizo
Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 146.13
Japanese yen, up from 144.32 late Thursday. The U.S. currency also
was changing hands at 1.7792 German marks, up from 1.7725.
</P>
<P>
In Mexico City in late trading, the dollar was worth 9.064
pesos, up from 9.021 Thursday. In New York late trading, the dollar
was worth 9.0570 pesos, up from 8.9800.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican peso fell to a record low against the dollar partly
because of pressure from the falling yen.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday: 1.4962 Swiss francs, up from 1.4930; 5.9650 French
francs, up from 5.9420; 1,755.75 Italian lire, up from 1,745.21;
and 1.5220 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5290.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6305 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6343 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
