<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bomb Rocks Peace in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- An explosion in the United
States embassy in the capital Friday has so far killed seven
people and injured 58 others, breaking the peace and tranquility
Tanzania has enjoyed for decades.
</P>
<P>
As the death toll is still rising, the police have tightened
security and started in-depth investigation into the blast,
caused by a bomb planted on an oil tanker which was entering the
gate of the embassy at around 10:45 a.m. (07:45GMT)
</P>
<P>
So far, nobody has claimed responsibility for the act and the
police have not arrested any one.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, which could be heard miles away, shattered the
office building in the embassy as well as structures in the
vicinity. "It was like an earthquake," a resident living close to
the embassy said.
</P>
<P>
The bomb killed several people instantly, throwing limbs in
all directions. About 20 meters from the gate, a bloody body
without head was seen in the grass. Flying glass also hurt people
in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
More than 22 cars and three motorcycles parked outside the
main building of the embassy were seen wrecked in flames.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference in the evening, Commissioner of Police
Wilson Mwansasu said that the U.S. ambassador was safe and sound
because he was not in the office when the explosion took place.
</P>
<P>
But Mwansasu did not say if there were any casualties of
Americans in the U.S. embassy.
</P>
<P>
Mwansasu said that heads of defense and security organs have
formed a five-man task force which was led by Director of
Criminal Investigation Adadi Rajabu.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner has appealed to citizens to provide clues and
asked them to be calm and continue with their work as usual. "The
security situation in Dar es Salaam is under control," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The government has yet to make any statement on the incident,
the first of its kind since the country became independent in
1961.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa is at a meeting in Zimbabwe
discussing the the Democratic Congo conflict with leaders of
other African countries, while Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye is
attending the budget session of the National Assembly in the
central city of Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ambassadors were summoned by the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs and International Cooperation for an urgent meeting
Friday afternoon. Spokesman for the ministry Simeon Ileta
declined to comment on the bombing. "We are going to tell you
when we are ready," he said.
</P>
<P>
A foreign ministry official said a statement is expected to
come out on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
A similar incident occurred almost at the same time in the
Kenyan capital of Nairobi, leaving at least 70 people dead and
more than 1,000 others injured.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has condemned the two bombings,
saying these terrorist attacks are "abhorrent" and "inhuman."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. Air Force is sending at least two military
aircraft with a surgical team and medical evacuation personnel to
Tanzania and Kenya following the bombings.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Secretary General, Kofi Annan, who is now
in Portugal for a visit, said the incidents are heartless and
constitute indiscriminate terrorism against innocent civilians.
He extended deep condolences to the families and governments
concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consequences of Iraqi Non-Cooperation Not Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.N. Security
Council source said Friday that the Council did not discuss the
consequences of Iraq's decision to suspend cooperation with U.N.
arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's suspension of cooperation was a major topic at the
Council's informal consultations on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq early this year was warned of the "severe consequences" if
it violates the Memorandum of Understanding it signed with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in February which defused a crisis
relating to arms inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's decision to suspend cooperation only "contravenes" the
accord while it has not yet led to any action, and in that sense
this cannot be clearly defined as violation or breach of
international law, the source said.
</P>
<P>
"That was the perception of the Council", he said, adding that
in choosing the proper word to describe the Iraqi decision, the
Council had found the differencies between "violation" and
"contravention".
</P>
<P>
What the source said is in line with the spirits of the
statements made by the Council President and the Secretary-General
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While rejecting Iraq's announcement as "totally unacceptable",
Council President Danio Turk of Slovania said that the move was
taken after a period of improved cooperation and some tangible
progress and the Council intended to respond favorably to future
progress made in the disarmament progress.
</P>
<P>
The Council called for an early resumption of dialogue between
the U.N. Special Commission for disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM,
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said his judgement is that the
Iraqi position on the matter "is not a closed one".
</P>
<P>
"Rather than allowing this situation to deteriorate into a
crisis, the Security Council should seek to engage with the Iraqi
authorities in order to resolve the problem."
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the council make a comprehensive review of
the entire issue by involving a more direct dialogue with Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
