<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Satisfied with Cambodian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan is satisfied with the recent elections in Cambodia, his
spokesman said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the spokesman said: "The
Secretary-General is pleased that elections to the National
Assembly in Cambodia were held on schedule on 26 July."
</P>
<P>
Noting with satisfaction that the polling process was primarily
peaceful and orderly, Annan congratulates the Cambodian people on
the overwhelming turnout of voters, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General hopes that all political parties will
resolve outstanding problems through dialogue and due process. The
objective should be the formation of a government that fully
reflects the wish of the Cambodian people for reconciliation,
pluralism and development," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The elections were conducted under international observation.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary results announced on Wednesday, the
ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP) led by the incumbent
co-premier Hun Sen won over 2.03 million votes, followed by
Funcinpec of Prince Norodom Ranariddh with 1.55 million votes, and
the opposition Sam Rainsy Party ((SRP) with 690,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
The CPP, failing to gain the required two-third majority in the
122 seat National Assembly, has to form a coalition with Funcinpec
or SRP or both.
</P>
<P>
The new National Assembly is expected to convene on September
24 before the formation of the government in early October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
