<HEADLINE> Judiciary Committee's Democrats Select Ethics Lawyer for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Democrats of the House of
Representatives have chosen a former ethics committee lawyer to
head any inquiry into U.S. President Bill Clinton's conduct should
special prosecutor Kenneth Starr send Congress a report on his
obstruction-of-justice investigation.
</P>
<P>
Ranking Democrat John Conyers of Michigan has hired veteran
Washington lawyer Abbe Lowell, former outside counsel to the
Committee on Standards of Official Conduct, The Associated Press
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lowell's firm, Brand Lowell &AMP; Ryan, specializes in government
ethics law.
</P>
<P>
Lowell fills the fourth and final position allotted committee
Democrats out of the 18 new staff jobs Republican leaders earlier
this year authorized for the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
Democrats have also hired investigative counsels Kevin Simpson,
a 10-year veteran of the Justice Department and Steve Reich, a
former federal public defender in Greenbelt, Maryland. Also
joining the team is press secretary James Jordan, who handled
media relations for Democrats during the Senate's campaign
fundraising investigation of Clinton last year.
</P>
<P>
With his share of the 1.3 million dollars allotted the
Judiciary Committee, Chairman Henry Hyde, a Republican, has hired
nine investigators for the majority. He is permitted five more.
</P>
<P>
Lowell, a graduate of Columbia University law school, has
served in the Justice Department and the U.N. High Commissioner
for Human Rights. He also has been a legal commentator for NBC's
Washington affiliate, WRC-TV, and a columnist for Legal Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
