<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Bomb Blast Shocks Kenyans in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- It was just like every weekend
morning, when people do their shopping in the city center of
Nairobi, Kenya's capital, with vehicles shuttling on busy
streets.
</P>
<P>
But as the clock ticked 10:35 a.m. local time, a deafening
explosion was heard in nearly the whole city.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, believed to be a car bomb, near the U.S.
embassy in the city center, claimed about 100 lives and injured
more than 1,000, local sources told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
About 50 people were said to be killed on the spot.
</P>
<P>
So far the exact death toll is still not available.
</P>
<P>
Ufundi House -- a five-storey office block between the U.S.
embassy and the 22-story Cooperative House, was turned into a
pile of debris, with fumes and fires swallowing up cars and
buildings nearby.
</P>
<P>
The whole rear wall of the U.S. embassy was gone, revealing
only five rows of smoke-blackened rooms.
</P>
<P>
Panic-stricken people, many of them with blood in heads, arms
or other parts of their bodies, ran for their lives in all
directions.
</P>
<P>
Matatus (local mini-buses) were seen dashing out from the
blast area, in doomsday-like craziness.
</P>
<P>
Two coaches full of passengers were rendered into horrifying
skeletons, with all glass gone, and about 20 dead immediately as
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Roads around the U.S. embassy were bloodstained and scattered
with pieces of broken window frames, furniture and stones. Glass
on almost all windows within 100 meters of the blast was also
blown away.
</P>
<P>
Ambulances and police vehicles were shuttling from the scene
to hospitals and vice versa in the city well into the night, and
several junctions were closed off by policemen, while helicopters
were hovering over the tragedy scene, coordinating the rescue
work on the ground.
</P>
<P>
U.S. embassy spokesman Chris Scharf told Xinhua by phone in
the evening that eight Americans, including two women and one
child, were killed by the bombing and another 15 wounded with one
still missing.
</P>
<P>
Both U.S. Ambassador to Kenya, Prudence Bushnell and Kenyan
Trade Minister Joseph Kamotho have sustained slight injuries.
</P>
<P>
They were having a meeting in Kamotho's office in the raided
building at the time of the blast.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of rescue workers including soldiers, firemen,
police, international aid workers, were still looking for victims
under the rubble. The rescue work was expected to last several
days.
</P>
<P>
"The rescue is going on. We are doing everything possible to
help those wounded and... to make sure everyone moved out of the
ruins," said Scharf.
</P>
<P>
All the main hospitals in Nairobi are now full of victims,
said eye-witnesses. Blood donators lining up in long queues
before major hospitals in the city after a TV announcement was
broadcast appealing for blood donations.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi Friday evening inspected the
blast scene and visited victims at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
He said he was deeply shocked and condemned the attack, vowing
to try best "to bring the perpetrators of the heinous crime to
book."
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan police said in the evening that they highly suspect
that the bomb blast is a terrorist attack aimed at the Americans.
</P>
<P>
Another bomb explosion rocked the U.S. embassy in Dar es
Salaam, the capital of Tanzania around the same time, at least
killing seven people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
