<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Arms Monitors Working as Usual in Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 7 (Xinhua)-- U.N. arms monitors went
out for work as usual today in Baghdad for the second straight
day although Iraq announced Wednesday its suspension of
cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
scrapping Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq refuses to have any dealing with U.N. teams that make
checks, with little advance notice, of sites where they suspect
weapons or weapons-related activities might be found, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Special Committee,led by Australian Richard Butler, has
currently 100 staff in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion of the Special Committee on Iraq's disarmament
would be decisive for the Security Council to consider lifting of
the eight-year sanction against Iraq imposed after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Security Council Thursday said that
Iraq's announcement Wednesday was "totally unacceptable", and it
urged Baghdad "not to implement its decision."
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the announcement "contravenes the
relevant Security Council resolutions and the memorandum of
understanding" signed in February by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980808.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan President Asks Kabila to Justify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimingu Friday asked Democratic Congo leader Laurent Kabila to
justify his allegations that Rwanda is supporting the rebellion
in the east of former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Zambia for Zimbabwe to attend an emergent
regional summit after his three-day stay here, Bizimingu told
reporters at the Lusaka International Airport that Rwanda has no
interest in disrupting peace in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
He denied that Rwanda is behind the on-going rebellion in the
eastern towns of former Zaire, saying that at the summit,
regional leaders will ask president Kabila to clearly elaborate
on the true picture of the situation in his country.
</P>
<P>
Bizimingu, who arrived in Zambia Wednesday for a three-day
state visit, flew out on the same plane with Zambian President
Frederick Chiluba for the Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe's picturesque
resort town bordering on Zambia.
</P>
<P>
In the past several days, Congo (K) has been blaming the
latest fightings on its ethnic Tutsi Banyamulenge community and
the soldiers from Rwanda's Tutsi-dominated army. The Kinshasa
government also accused Uganda of getting involved in the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
While at a news conference Thursday evening, Kabila stopped
short of a declaration of war against Rwanda, which backed him
last year on his way to toppling former dictator Mobutu Sese Seko
after a seven-month war.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Congolese people to prepare for a long war
and noted that the war should be taken to Rwanda, saying: "we
should prepare for a long drawn-out war, a people's war in which
the entire people should defend its homeland and sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
However, both Rwanda and Uganda have denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
During an official talk with Zambia President Frederick
Chiluba in Lusaka Wednesday, Rwandan President Bizimingu said
that "for the time being, there is no particular reason for his
country to get involved" in Congo's conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government also said Thursday evening that it
wishes to reiterate its policy of good neighborlihood with and
non-interference in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The emergent summit was called in order that the regional
leaders could brainstorm on the inflamable situation in Congo (K)
and the flare-ups in Angola where the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) and the government have begun
amassing troops to resume fighting.
</P>
<P>
The two conflicts and persistent allegations that Rwanda is
backing the Congo rebellion and that Zambia is supplying Angola's
rebel UNITA movement with arms, have created uncertainty on the
future of peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the presidents of Rwanda, Zambia, Namibia,
Tanzania and Uganda have confirmed that they will join host
President Robert Mugabe Friday for the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
