<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Announces 5-Day Mourning for Bomb Victims  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President President Moi
declared Friday evening a five-day period of nationwide mourning
</P>
<P>
The whole death toll of the blast has increased to nearly 100
and more than 1,000 wounded have been rushed to hospitals, local
media estimated. So far at least 60 were confirmed dead.
</P>
<P>
During the mourning period, all other social activities such
as school drama festivals stand suspended and flags at all
governmental institutions will fly at half-mast, said Moi.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that U.S. Ambassador Prudence Bushnell got
injured in the bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
Both Bushnell and Kenyan Trade Minister Joseph Kamotho have
sustained slight injuries. Kamotho's office was hosted in the
bombed 22-story Cooperative House just next to the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Moi toured the bombing scene during the peak of
rescue efforts and then visited some wounded including Trade
Minister Joseph Kamotho at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president urged the public to keep calm.
</P>
<P>
The extent of the damage, he explained, will be assessed first
before Kenya could ask for international assistance.
</P>
<P>
The government in a statement issued from State House said the
attack was an act of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"I have directed the security organs to do everything possible
to respond to this situation effectively," said Moi, condemning
the attack and asked for anybody with information that could lead
to arrest of perpetrators, to forward it to police.
</P>
<P>
A number of people - either alive or dead - were still trapped
in the building.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers said they expected the death toll to jump
drastically.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people were also injured when window glass and
pieces of stones shattered from the scene and nearby buildings
flung onto pavements and pathways.
</P>
<P>
Many buildings in the radius of 400 meters from the blast area
had windows and anti-burglar grills shattered. Nearby Cooperative
and National banks were also devastated.
</P>
<P>
The roof of Kenya Railways Headquarters, about 100 meters from
the explosion site, caved in, injuring many.
</P>
<P>
A security official said the bombs were believed to be in a
van parked in an alley between Cooperative House and the embassy.
</P>
</TEXT>
