<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blast Paralyzes Business in Nairobi  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Business in the Kenyan capital
Nairobi was paralyzed in mid-morning Friday by the bomb blasts
</P>
<P>
About 100 people were feared dead and more than 1,000 were
seriously wounded during the blasts, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Moments after the explosion, many people in private and
government offices closed business for the day.
</P>
<P>
The city center was almost deserted in the afternoon, when the
central business district is usually very busy as residents go
shopping for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Trading and other operations at the Nairobi Stock Exchange
(NSE) were stopped when traders left the trading floor after the
bomb blasts.
</P>
<P>
Officials said trading had started as usual until the blasts
shook the city. Dealers joined other curious Kenyans in the rush
to "safe exit" following the deafening bang of the bomb.
</P>
<P>
The NSE was unmanned for most of the afternoon as the workers
seemed to have left for home. Only a few deals were said to have
concluded before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Normal operations were also paralyzed as hospitals prepared to
take in casualties of the blasts.
</P>
<P>
Vehicles on Haile Selassie, Moi and Harambee avenues were
badly damaged and their occupants seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
The damage virtually made walking in town impossible as the
streets were littered with broken glass and pieces of paper
documents blown from the affected buildings.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people thronged the scene, many of them weeping
uncontrollably as they tried to find out the fate of their
friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
Buildings near the scene had all window panes broken and some
parts of the walls were partially destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Cooperative House, which houses the Teachers Service
Commission, had all its window panes blown up. Many of those who
work in the building were seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
The American Embassy was partially ripped through and rescuers
could be seen taking out the injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
